(108, NULL, NULL, 'technology/2025/oct/16/google-ai-overviews-italian-news-publishers-demand-investigation', 'Italian news publishers demand investigation into Google’s AI Overviews', 'Newspaper federation says ‘traffic killer’ feature violates legislation and threatens to destroy media diversity', 'Italian news publishers are calling for an investigation into Google’s AI Overviews, arguing that the search engine’s AI-generated summaries feature is a “traffic killer” that threatens their survival. FIEG, the Italian federation of newspaper publishers, said it has submitted a formal complaint to Agcom, Italy’s communications watchdog. Similar complaints have been filed in other EU countries. Coordinated by the European Newspaper Publishers’ Association, the aim is to push the European Commission to open an investigation against Google under the EU Digital Services Act. The threat posed by AI Overviews, which gives users information without them having to click through to the original source by summarising searches with a block of text at the top of the results page, is among the main concerns of European news outlets. FIEG said it was also worried about the more recent AI Mode, which takes information from multiple sources and presents them as a chatbot. The federation argues that the Google services “violate fundamental provisions of the digital services act, with detrimental effects on Italian users, consumers and businesses”. “Google is becoming a traffic killer,” FIEG said in a statement, adding that the products not only directly compete with content produced by publishing firms, but also “reduces their visibility and discoverability, and thus their advertising revenues”. “This has serious consequences for the economic sustainability and diversity of the media, with all the risks associated with a lack of transparency and the proliferation of disinformation in democratic debate,” the statement said. A study published in July by the UK-based Authoritas analytics company claimed AI Overviews, launched by Google last year, caused up to 80% fewer clickthroughs. The research, which was submitted as part of a legal complaint to the UK’s competition watchdog about the impact of Google AI Overviews, also found that links to YouTube – owned by Google’s parent company Alphabet – were more prominent compared with the normal search result system. A second study by the Pew Research Center, a US thinktank, also showed a big hit to referral traffic from Google AI Overviews, with users only clicking a link under an AI summary once every 100 times. Google claimed the studies were inaccurate and based on flawed methodology. Google AI Overviews arrived in Italy in March. In September, the country became the first in the EU to approve a comprehensive law regulating the use of artificial intelligence, including limiting child access and imposing prison terms on those who use the technology to cause harm, such as generating deepfakes. Giorgia Meloni’s government described the legislation, which aligns with the EU’s landmark AI Act, as a decisive move in influencing how AI is used across Italy.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2025/oct/16/google-ai-overviews-italian-news-publishers-demand-investigation', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/4facf3c2d97e936db3c14109c41fa75377ace05e/339_0_2433_1946/500.jpg', '2025-10-16 19:53:59', '{\"id\":\"technology\\/2025\\/oct\\/16\\/google-ai-overviews-italian-news-publishers-demand-investigation\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"technology\",\"sectionName\":\"Technology\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-16T12:53:59Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Italian news publishers demand investigation into Google\\u2019s AI Overviews\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/technology\\/2025\\/oct\\/16\\/google-ai-overviews-italian-news-publishers-demand-investigation\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/technology\\/2025\\/oct\\/16\\/google-ai-overviews-italian-news-publishers-demand-investigation\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Italian news publishers demand investigation into Google\\u2019s AI Overviews\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Newspaper federation says \\u2018traffic killer\\u2019 feature violates legislation and threatens to destroy media diversity<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"Newspaper federation says \\u2018traffic killer\\u2019 feature violates legislation and threatens to destroy media diversity\",\"byline\":\"Angela Giuffrida Rome correspondent\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"05ff4a8c9e0f030026ecb64ef861d1245bf88a99\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/05ff4a8c9e0f030026ecb64ef861d1245bf88a99\\/212_0_3004_2403\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"A general view of the Google homepage on a phone\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">The AI-generated summaries created in Google searches have \\u2018detrimental effects on Italian users, consumers and businesses\\u2019, according to FIEG.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Andrew Matthews\\/PA<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>Italian news publishers are calling for an investigation into Google\\u2019s AI Overviews, arguing that the search engine\\u2019s AI-generated summaries feature is a \\u201ctraffic killer\\u201d that threatens their survival.<\\/p> <p>FIEG, the Italian federation of newspaper publishers, said it has submitted a formal complaint to Agcom, Italy\\u2019s communications watchdog.<\\/p> <p>Similar complaints have been filed in other EU countries. Coordinated by the European Newspaper Publishers\\u2019 Association, the aim is to push the European Commission to open an investigation against Google under the EU Digital Services Act.<\\/p> <p>The <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/technology\\/2025\\/jul\\/24\\/ai-summaries-causing-devastating-drop-in-online-news-audiences-study-finds\\\">threat posed by AI Overviews<\\/a>, which gives users information without them having to click through to the original source by summarising searches with a block of text at the top of the results page, is among the main concerns of European news outlets.<\\/p> <p>FIEG said it was also worried about the more recent AI Mode, which takes information from multiple sources and presents them as a chatbot.<\\/p> <p>The federation argues that the Google services \\u201cviolate fundamental provisions of the digital services act, with detrimental effects on Italian users, consumers and businesses\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cGoogle is becoming a traffic killer,\\u201d FIEG said in a statement, adding that the products not only directly compete with content produced by publishing firms, but also \\u201creduces their visibility and discoverability, and thus their advertising revenues\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cThis has serious consequences for the economic sustainability and diversity of the media, with all the risks associated with a lack of transparency and the proliferation of disinformation in democratic debate,\\u201d the statement said.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/commentisfree\\/2025\\/oct\\/16\\/ai-creating-underclass-makers-tech-bubble-replaceable\\\">AI might be creating a \\u2018permanent underclass\\u2019 but it\\u2019s the makers of the tech bubble who are replaceable | Van Badham<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>A study published in July by the UK-based Authoritas analytics company claimed AI Overviews, launched by Google last year, caused <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/technology\\/2025\\/jul\\/24\\/ai-summaries-causing-devastating-drop-in-online-news-audiences-study-finds\\\">up to 80% fewer clickthroughs<\\/a>. The research, which was submitted as part of a legal complaint to the UK\\u2019s competition watchdog about the impact of Google AI Overviews, also found that links to YouTube \\u2013 owned by Google\\u2019s parent company Alphabet \\u2013 were more prominent compared with the normal search result system.<\\/p> <p>A second study by the Pew Research Center, a US thinktank, also showed a big hit to referral traffic from Google AI Overviews, with users only clicking a link under an AI summary once every 100 times.<\\/p> <p>Google claimed the studies were inaccurate and based on flawed methodology.<\\/p> <p>Google AI Overviews arrived in Italy in March. In September, the country became the first in the EU to approve a comprehensive law regulating the use of artificial intelligence, including limiting child access and imposing prison terms on those who use the technology to cause harm, such as generating deepfakes.<\\/p> <p>Giorgia Meloni\\u2019s government described the legislation, which aligns with the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/world\\/2023\\/dec\\/08\\/eu-agrees-historic-deal-with-worlds-first-laws-to-regulate-ai\\\">EU\\u2019s landmark AI Act<\\/a>, as a decisive move in influencing how AI is used across Italy.<\\/p>\",\"wordcount\":\"449\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-16T12:53:59Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-10-16T14:23:12Z\",\"newspaperEditionDate\":\"2025-10-17T00:00:00Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"UK\",\"publication\":\"The Guardian\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3em3b\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/4facf3c2d97e936db3c14109c41fa75377ace05e\\/339_0_2433_1946\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"Italian news publishers are calling for an investigation into Google\\u2019s AI Overviews, arguing that the search engine\\u2019s AI-generated summaries feature is a \\u201ctraffic killer\\u201d that threatens their survival. FIEG, the Italian federation of newspaper publishers, said it has submitted a formal complaint to Agcom, Italy\\u2019s communications watchdog. Similar complaints have been filed in other EU countries. Coordinated by the European Newspaper Publishers\\u2019 Association, the aim is to push the European Commission to open an investigation against Google under the EU Digital Services Act. The threat posed by AI Overviews, which gives users information without them having to click through to the original source by summarising searches with a block of text at the top of the results page, is among the main concerns of European news outlets. FIEG said it was also worried about the more recent AI Mode, which takes information from multiple sources and presents them as a chatbot. The federation argues that the Google services \\u201cviolate fundamental provisions of the digital services act, with detrimental effects on Italian users, consumers and businesses\\u201d. \\u201cGoogle is becoming a traffic killer,\\u201d FIEG said in a statement, adding that the products not only directly compete with content produced by publishing firms, but also \\u201creduces their visibility and discoverability, and thus their advertising revenues\\u201d. \\u201cThis has serious consequences for the economic sustainability and diversity of the media, with all the risks associated with a lack of transparency and the proliferation of disinformation in democratic debate,\\u201d the statement said. A study published in July by the UK-based Authoritas analytics company claimed AI Overviews, launched by Google last year, caused up to 80% fewer clickthroughs. The research, which was submitted as part of a legal complaint to the UK\\u2019s competition watchdog about the impact of Google AI Overviews, also found that links to YouTube \\u2013 owned by Google\\u2019s parent company Alphabet \\u2013 were more prominent compared with the normal search result system. A second study by the Pew Research Center, a US thinktank, also showed a big hit to referral traffic from Google AI Overviews, with users only clicking a link under an AI summary once every 100 times. Google claimed the studies were inaccurate and based on flawed methodology. Google AI Overviews arrived in Italy in March. In September, the country became the first in the EU to approve a comprehensive law regulating the use of artificial intelligence, including limiting child access and imposing prison terms on those who use the technology to cause harm, such as generating deepfakes. Giorgia Meloni\\u2019s government described the legislation, which aligns with the EU\\u2019s landmark AI Act, as a decisive move in influencing how AI is used across Italy.\",\"charCount\":\"2830\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/angela-giuffrida\\\">Angela Giuffrida<\\/a> Rome correspondent\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL);
