(137, NULL, NULL, 'us-news/2025/sep/14/fox-brian-kilmeade-apology-homelessness-comments', 'Fox News host apologizes for ‘extremely callous’ remarks on unhoused people', 'Calls rose for Brian Kilmeade to be fired after saying people facing homelessness and mental illness should be executed', 'Fox News host Brian Kilmeade apologized on Sunday for saying days earlier that people who are experiencing homelessness and mental illnesses should be executed – remarks that prompted calls for him to be fired. The host said his comments on Wednesday were “extremely callous”. Kilmeade’s about-face came amid a climate in which people across the US are either being fired from or disciplined at their jobs amid a coordinated effort to clamp down on commentary that is critical about Turning Point USA’s executive director, Charlie Kirk, who was shot to death at an event in Utah on Wednesday. Mere hours before the conservative political activist was killed, while on the rightwing Fox News program Fox &amp; Friends, Kilmeade and two other hosts were discussing the killing of 23-year-old Iryna Zarutska, a Ukrainian woman who was fatally stabbed on a commuter train in North Carolina in August. The man charged with killing Zarutska at random in Charlotte had reportedly been diagnosed with schizophrenia and had 14 prior criminal arrests. Surveillance video of the Zarutska’s killing went viral online. During the Fox and Friends appearance on Wednesday discussing Zarutska’s death, co-host Lawrence Jones said unhoused people with mental illness should either accept the publicly funded programs to help in their situation or be jailed. “Involuntary lethal injection or something,” Kilmeade responded to Jones. “Just kill ’em.” Kilmeade faced widespread backlash for his comments. Among those to respond was California’s Democratic governor, Gavin Newsom, who on social media posted a biblical verse reading: “Whoever closes his ear to the cry of the poor will himself call out and not be answered.” On Sunday morning, during an appearance with Jones on Fox &amp; Friends Weekends, Kilmeade apologized for his idea of killing those who are unhoused and mentally ill. “I wrongly said they should get lethal injections” on Wednesday, Kilmeade said. “I apologize for that extremely callous remark. I am obviously aware that not all mentally ill, homeless people act as the perpetrator did in North Carolina – and that so many homeless people deserve our empathy and compassion.” Unlike others who were deemed to have made offensive comments about Kirk’s death, Kilmeade remained employed by Fox News. His professional fate struck a sharp contrast with Dowd, a veteran political analyst fired by MSNBC for suggesting on air that Kirk’s far-right rhetoric may have contributed to the violence that killed him. “Hateful thoughts lead to hateful words, which then lead to hateful actions,” Dowd said. “You can’t stop with these sort of awful thats you have and then saying these awful words and then not expect awful actions to take place.” The network and Dowd each separately issued apologies. But in a Substack article published on Friday, Dowd said he had been victimized by a “rightwing media mob” and that words he spoke before knowing Kirk had been the target of a shooting were misconstrued. “Kilmeade is advocating for extrajudicial killings on FOX, yet Matthew Dowd was fired by MSNBC [for] pointing out Charlie Kirk’s dangerous rhetoric,” author Shannon Watts said on X. “This moral asymmetry in the media and online is destroying democracy.” Zarutska’s killing has become an inflection point for Republicans, who are blaming Democratic policies in certain US cities for such crimes. Studies show that people experiencing homelessness are more likely to be victims of violent crime than perpetrators. And other studies have shown that mental illness is not a predictor of future violence.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/sep/14/fox-brian-kilmeade-apology-homelessness-comments', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/5b7002097d15a54ffde881bcd5ce5cb3924d2f63/183_0_2238_1791/500.jpg', '2025-09-15 00:00:32', '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/14\\/fox-brian-kilmeade-apology-homelessness-comments\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-09-14T17:00:32Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Fox News host apologizes for \\u2018extremely callous\\u2019 remarks on unhoused people\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/14\\/fox-brian-kilmeade-apology-homelessness-comments\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/14\\/fox-brian-kilmeade-apology-homelessness-comments\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Fox News host apologizes for \\u2018extremely callous\\u2019 remarks on unhoused people\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Calls rose for Brian Kilmeade to be fired after saying people facing homelessness and mental illness should be executed<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"Calls rose for Brian Kilmeade to be fired after saying people facing homelessness and mental illness should be executed\",\"byline\":\"Jos\\u00e9 Olivares\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"5b7002097d15a54ffde881bcd5ce5cb3924d2f63\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/5b7002097d15a54ffde881bcd5ce5cb3924d2f63\\/183_0_2238_1791\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"man in suit looks ahead, smiling\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">Fox &amp; Friends host Brian Kilmeade in New York City on 17 October 2024.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Ted Shaffrey\\/AP<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/fox-news\\\">Fox News<\\/a> host Brian Kilmeade apologized on Sunday for saying days earlier that people who are experiencing <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/society\\/homelessness\\\">homelessness<\\/a> and mental illnesses should be executed \\u2013 remarks that prompted calls for him to be fired.<\\/p> <p>The host said his comments on Wednesday were \\u201cextremely callous\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>Kilmeade\\u2019s about-face came amid a climate in which people across the US are either <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/13\\/charlie-kirk-shooting-people-fired-social-media\\\">being fired from or disciplined<\\/a> at their jobs amid a coordinated effort to clamp down on commentary that is critical about Turning Point USA\\u2019s executive director, Charlie Kirk, who was <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/charlie-kirk-shooting\\\">shot to death<\\/a> at an event in Utah on Wednesday.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/13\\/charlie-kirk-shooting-people-fired-social-media\\\">Several people fired after clampdown on speech over Charlie Kirk shooting<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>Mere hours before the conservative political activist was killed, while on the rightwing Fox News program Fox &amp; Friends, Kilmeade and two other hosts were discussing the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/09\\/north-carolina-ukraine-woman-stabbing\\\">killing of 23-year-old Iryna Zarutska<\\/a>, a Ukrainian woman who was fatally stabbed on a commuter train in North Carolina in August.<\\/p> <p>The man charged with killing Zarutska at random in Charlotte had reportedly been diagnosed with schizophrenia and had 14 prior criminal arrests. Surveillance video of the Zarutska\\u2019s killing went viral online.<\\/p> <p>During the Fox and Friends appearance on Wednesday discussing Zarutska\\u2019s death, co-host Lawrence Jones said unhoused people with mental illness should either accept the publicly funded programs to help in their situation or be jailed.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cInvoluntary lethal injection or something,\\u201d Kilmeade responded to Jones. \\u201cJust kill \\u2019em.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>Kilmeade faced widespread backlash for his comments. Among those to respond was California\\u2019s Democratic governor, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/gavin-newsom\\\">Gavin Newsom<\\/a>, who on social media posted a biblical verse reading: \\u201cWhoever closes his ear to the cry of the poor will himself call out and not be answered.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>On Sunday morning, during an appearance with Jones on Fox &amp; Friends Weekends, Kilmeade apologized for his idea of killing those who are unhoused and mentally ill.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cI wrongly said they should get lethal injections\\u201d on Wednesday, Kilmeade said. \\u201cI apologize for that extremely callous remark. I am obviously aware that not all mentally ill, homeless people act as the perpetrator did in North Carolina \\u2013 and that so many homeless people deserve our empathy and compassion.\\u201d<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/14\\/trump-administration-charlie-kirk-news-updates-latest\\\">Unlike others<\\/a> who were deemed to have made offensive comments about Kirk\\u2019s death, Kilmeade remained employed by Fox News.<\\/p> <p>His professional fate struck a sharp contrast with Dowd, a veteran political analyst <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/11\\/msnbc-fires-matthew-dowd-charlie-kirk-shooting\\\">fired<\\/a> by MSNBC for suggesting on air that Kirk\\u2019s far-right rhetoric may have contributed to the violence that killed him.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/11\\/msnbc-fires-matthew-dowd-charlie-kirk-shooting\\\">MSNBC fires analyst Matthew Dowd over Charlie Kirk shooting remarks<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>\\u201cHateful thoughts lead to hateful words, which then lead to hateful actions,\\u201d Dowd said. \\u201cYou can\\u2019t stop with these sort of awful thats you have and then saying these awful words and then not expect awful actions to take place.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>The network and Dowd each separately issued apologies. But in a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/matthewdowd.substack.com\\/p\\/a-time-to-see-with-new-eyes?r=95pvg&amp;utm_medium=ios&amp;triedRedirect=true\\\">Substack article<\\/a> published on Friday, Dowd said he had been victimized by a \\u201crightwing media mob\\u201d and that words he spoke before knowing Kirk had been the target of a shooting were misconstrued.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cKilmeade is advocating for extrajudicial killings on FOX, yet Matthew Dowd was fired by MSNBC [for] pointing out Charlie Kirk\\u2019s dangerous rhetoric,\\u201d author Shannon Watts <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/x.com\\/shannonrwatts\\/status\\/1966871593948483781\\\">said on X<\\/a>. \\u201cThis moral asymmetry in the media and online is destroying democracy.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>Zarutska\\u2019s killing has become an inflection point for Republicans, who are blaming Democratic policies in certain US cities for such crimes.<\\/p> <p>Studies show that people experiencing homelessness are more likely to be <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/connect.springerpub.com\\/content\\/sgrvv\\/29\\/1\\/122\\\">victims<\\/a> of violent crime than perpetrators. And other <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/jamanetwork.com\\/journals\\/jamapsychiatry\\/fullarticle\\/210191#:~:text=Results%C2%A0%20Bivariate,severe%20mental%20illness.\\\">studies<\\/a> have shown that mental illness is not a predictor of future violence.<\\/p>\",\"wordcount\":\"571\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-09-14T17:00:32Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-09-14T17:01:31Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3828z\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"true\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/5b7002097d15a54ffde881bcd5ce5cb3924d2f63\\/183_0_2238_1791\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"Fox News host Brian Kilmeade apologized on Sunday for saying days earlier that people who are experiencing homelessness and mental illnesses should be executed \\u2013 remarks that prompted calls for him to be fired. The host said his comments on Wednesday were \\u201cextremely callous\\u201d. Kilmeade\\u2019s about-face came amid a climate in which people across the US are either being fired from or disciplined at their jobs amid a coordinated effort to clamp down on commentary that is critical about Turning Point USA\\u2019s executive director, Charlie Kirk, who was shot to death at an event in Utah on Wednesday. Mere hours before the conservative political activist was killed, while on the rightwing Fox News program Fox &amp; Friends, Kilmeade and two other hosts were discussing the killing of 23-year-old Iryna Zarutska, a Ukrainian woman who was fatally stabbed on a commuter train in North Carolina in August. The man charged with killing Zarutska at random in Charlotte had reportedly been diagnosed with schizophrenia and had 14 prior criminal arrests. Surveillance video of the Zarutska\\u2019s killing went viral online. During the Fox and Friends appearance on Wednesday discussing Zarutska\\u2019s death, co-host Lawrence Jones said unhoused people with mental illness should either accept the publicly funded programs to help in their situation or be jailed. \\u201cInvoluntary lethal injection or something,\\u201d Kilmeade responded to Jones. \\u201cJust kill \\u2019em.\\u201d Kilmeade faced widespread backlash for his comments. Among those to respond was California\\u2019s Democratic governor, Gavin Newsom, who on social media posted a biblical verse reading: \\u201cWhoever closes his ear to the cry of the poor will himself call out and not be answered.\\u201d On Sunday morning, during an appearance with Jones on Fox &amp; Friends Weekends, Kilmeade apologized for his idea of killing those who are unhoused and mentally ill. \\u201cI wrongly said they should get lethal injections\\u201d on Wednesday, Kilmeade said. \\u201cI apologize for that extremely callous remark. I am obviously aware that not all mentally ill, homeless people act as the perpetrator did in North Carolina \\u2013 and that so many homeless people deserve our empathy and compassion.\\u201d Unlike others who were deemed to have made offensive comments about Kirk\\u2019s death, Kilmeade remained employed by Fox News. His professional fate struck a sharp contrast with Dowd, a veteran political analyst fired by MSNBC for suggesting on air that Kirk\\u2019s far-right rhetoric may have contributed to the violence that killed him. \\u201cHateful thoughts lead to hateful words, which then lead to hateful actions,\\u201d Dowd said. \\u201cYou can\\u2019t stop with these sort of awful thats you have and then saying these awful words and then not expect awful actions to take place.\\u201d The network and Dowd each separately issued apologies. But in a Substack article published on Friday, Dowd said he had been victimized by a \\u201crightwing media mob\\u201d and that words he spoke before knowing Kirk had been the target of a shooting were misconstrued. \\u201cKilmeade is advocating for extrajudicial killings on FOX, yet Matthew Dowd was fired by MSNBC [for] pointing out Charlie Kirk\\u2019s dangerous rhetoric,\\u201d author Shannon Watts said on X. \\u201cThis moral asymmetry in the media and online is destroying democracy.\\u201d Zarutska\\u2019s killing has become an inflection point for Republicans, who are blaming Democratic policies in certain US cities for such crimes. Studies show that people experiencing homelessness are more likely to be victims of violent crime than perpetrators. And other studies have shown that mental illness is not a predictor of future violence.\",\"charCount\":\"3596\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/jose-olivares\\\">Jos\\u00e9 Olivares<\\/a>\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL),
(138, NULL, NULL, 'media/2025/oct/06/who-is-bari-weiss-cbs-news', 'Who is Bari Weiss, the new editor-in-chief of CBS News?', 'Ex-NYT writer who launched ‘anti-woke commentary’ website will report directly to Paramount Skydance head David Ellison', 'Paramount Skydance has appointed Bari Weiss, a former New York Times opinion writer who launched an “anti-woke” commentary website, as editor-in-chief of CBS News. Five years after an acrimonious exit from the New York Times, Weiss, 41, has been installed at the top of one of the most venerated institutions in US news – solidifying the meteoric rise of a divisive figure in media. She will report directly to David Ellison, the son of the billionaire tech mogul Larry Ellison and head of Paramount Skydance, the company that owns CBS News, which has acquired the Free Press, Weiss’s media startup. As editor-in-chief, Weiss will probably play a major role in shaping news coverage at the network. Where did Weiss get her start? Weiss held editorial roles at Jewish news outlets early in her career, including Haaretz, the Forward and Tablet. In 2013, she joined the opinion staff at the Wall Street Journal. In 2017, she joined Brett Stephens in moving to the New York Times’ opinion desk, where she started writing her own column. What did she do at the New York Times? As a journalist at the New York Times, Weiss developed a reputation for both criticizing Donald Trump in his first term and cracking down on the left’s cancel culture, from cultural appropriation to protests on college campuses. In the swirls of the #MeToo movement, she penned a viral op-ed defending comedian Aziz Ansari, who was accused of sexual misconduct in an anonymous essay. Weiss said at the time that the essay “transforms what ought to be a movement for women’s empowerment into an emblem for female helplessness”. Why did Weiss leave the Times? Weiss’s departure from the Times increased her profile even more. In July 2020, she published a public resignation letter, addressed to Times publisher AG Schulzberger, where she accused the company of becoming partisan, and reporting stories “to satisfy the narrowest of audiences”. She also said she was “the subject of constant bullying by colleagues who disagree with my views”. The Times said at the time it was committed to “fostering an environment of honest, searching and empathetic dialogue” between its employees. What is the Free Press? Months after her departure from the Times, Weiss started a newsletter called Common Sense. The newsletter eventually expanded into a media startup, the Free Press, which publishes newsletters and podcasts. The company received backing from investors including the venture capitalists Marc Andreesen and David Sacks and former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz. At the Free Press, Weiss published controversial reports and series, including the podcast The Witch Trials of JK Rowling, about the Harry Potter author and her clash with liberals over her views on trans people, and a report on the Columbia pro-Palestine encampments with the headline “Camping Out at Columbia’s Communist Coachella”. The author of a book titled How to Fight Anti-Semitism, Weiss is a longtime, staunch supporter of Israel and has utilized the Free Press to defend the country during the war in Gaza. Why is Paramount Skydance acquiring the Free Press? Skydance Media made an agreement with the Trump administration that its content will promote a “diversity of viewpoints” in the company’s bid to the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to merge with Paramount Global. The FCC agreed to the merger in July, which saw Skydance pay $8bn to merge with Paramount, making Ellison in charge of the new Paramount Skydance company. Ahead of the merger, Paramount Global also paid $16m to Trump to settle a defamation lawsuit the president had filed against 60 Minutes, a move that was largely criticized by media watchdogs. Paramount also announced the 2026 cancellation of Stephen Colbert’s show, which was widely seen as a capitulation to Trump. Brendan Carr, chairman of the Federal Communications Commissions, which greenlit the merger, said that he was “pleased” with commitments the company made to reform CBS. In a letter to Carr, Skydance said it would ensure that the new company’s “array of news and entertainment programming embodies a diversity of viewpoints across the political and ideological spectrum”. Paramount Skydance is also reportedly preparing to make a bid to buy Warner Bros Discovery, the company that owns CNN. On Monday, Ellison suggested the acquisition of the Free Press – and Weiss’s appointment as editor-in-chief – would help CBS News to reach “the majority of the country”.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/media/2025/oct/06/who-is-bari-weiss-cbs-news', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/d20eacbe6763e8b3d95f35a3db97ec579b01e189/520_0_5200_4160/500.jpg', '2025-10-06 19:59:28', '{\"id\":\"media\\/2025\\/oct\\/06\\/who-is-bari-weiss-cbs-news\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"media\",\"sectionName\":\"Media\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-06T12:59:28Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Who is Bari Weiss, the new editor-in-chief of CBS News?\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/06\\/who-is-bari-weiss-cbs-news\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/06\\/who-is-bari-weiss-cbs-news\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Who is Bari Weiss, the new editor-in-chief of CBS News?\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Ex-NYT writer who launched \\u2018anti-woke commentary\\u2019 website will report directly to Paramount Skydance head David Ellison<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"Ex-NYT writer who launched \\u2018anti-woke commentary\\u2019 website will report directly to Paramount Skydance head David Ellison\",\"byline\":\"Lauren Aratani\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"d20eacbe6763e8b3d95f35a3db97ec579b01e189\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/d20eacbe6763e8b3d95f35a3db97ec579b01e189\\/520_0_5200_4160\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Bari Weiss in Los Angeles in September 2023. \\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">Bari Weiss in Los Angeles in September 2023. <br><\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Francine Orr\\/Los Angeles Times\\/Getty Images<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>Paramount Skydance has appointed Bari Weiss, a former New York Times opinion writer who launched an \\u201canti-woke\\u201d commentary website, as <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/06\\/bari-weiss-cbs-news-paramount-free-press\\\">editor-in-chief of CBS News<\\/a>.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/ng-interactive\\/2025\\/sep\\/10\\/bari-weiss-cbs\\\">Disgruntled NYT journalist to \\u2018anti-woke\\u2019 power grab: how far can Bari Weiss go?<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>Five years after an acrimonious exit from the<em> <\\/em>New York Times, Weiss, 41, has been installed at the top of one of the most venerated institutions in US news \\u2013 solidifying the meteoric rise of a divisive figure in media.<\\/p> <p>She will report directly to David Ellison, the son of the billionaire tech mogul Larry Ellison and head of Paramount Skydance, the company that owns CBS News, which has acquired the Free Press, Weiss\\u2019s media startup.<\\/p> <p>As editor-in-chief, Weiss will probably play a major role in shaping news coverage at the network.<\\/p> <h2>Where did Weiss get her start?<\\/h2> <p>Weiss held editorial roles at Jewish news outlets early in her career, including Haaretz, the Forward and Tablet. In 2013, she joined the opinion staff at the Wall Street Journal. In 2017, she joined Brett Stephens in moving to the New York Times\\u2019 opinion desk, where she started writing her own column.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/06\\/bari-weiss-cbs-news-paramount-free-press\\\">Bari Weiss named editor-in-chief of CBS News as Paramount buys Free Press startup<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <h2>What did she do at the New York Times?<\\/h2> <p>As a journalist at the New York Times, Weiss developed a reputation for both criticizing Donald Trump in his first term and cracking down on the left\\u2019s cancel culture, from <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/2017\\/08\\/30\\/opinion\\/cultural-appropriation.html\\\">cultural appropriation<\\/a> to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/2018\\/03\\/07\\/opinion\\/were-all-fascists-now.html\\\">protests<\\/a> on college campuses.<\\/p> <p>In the swirls of the #MeToo movement, she penned a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/2018\\/01\\/15\\/opinion\\/aziz-ansari-babe-sexual-harassment.html\\\">viral op-ed<\\/a> defending comedian Aziz Ansari, who was accused of sexual misconduct in an anonymous essay. Weiss said at the time that the essay \\u201ctransforms what ought to be a movement for women\\u2019s empowerment into an emblem for female helplessness\\u201d.<\\/p> <h2>Why did Weiss leave the Times?<\\/h2> <p>Weiss\\u2019s departure from the Times increased her profile even more. In July 2020, she published a public resignation letter, addressed to Times publisher AG Schulzberger, where she accused the company of becoming partisan, and reporting stories \\u201cto satisfy the narrowest of audiences\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>She also said she was \\u201cthe subject of constant bullying by colleagues who disagree with my views\\u201d. The Times said at the time it was committed to \\u201cfostering an environment of honest, searching and empathetic dialogue\\u201d between its employees.<\\/p> <h2>What is the Free Press?<\\/h2> <p>Months after her departure from the Times, Weiss started a newsletter called Common Sense. The newsletter eventually expanded into a media startup, the Free Press, which publishes newsletters and podcasts. The company received backing from investors including the venture capitalists Marc Andreesen and David Sacks and former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz.<\\/p> <p>At the Free Press, Weiss published controversial reports and series, including the podcast The Witch Trials of JK Rowling, about the Harry Potter author and her clash with liberals over her views on trans people, and a report on the Columbia pro-Palestine encampments with the headline \\u201cCamping Out at Columbia\\u2019s Communist Coachella\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>The author of a book titled How to Fight Anti-Semitism, Weiss is a longtime, staunch supporter of Israel and has utilized the Free Press to defend the country during the war in Gaza.<\\/p> <h2>Why is Paramount Skydance acquiring the Free Press?<\\/h2> <p>Skydance Media made an agreement with the Trump administration that its content will promote a \\u201cdiversity of viewpoints\\u201d in the company\\u2019s bid to the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to merge with Paramount Global.<\\/p> <p>The FCC agreed to the merger in July, which saw Skydance <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/jul\\/24\\/paramount-skydance-merger-fcc\\\">pay<\\/a> $8bn to merge with Paramount, making Ellison in charge of the new Paramount Skydance company.<\\/p> <p>Ahead of the merger, Paramount Global also <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/jul\\/02\\/paramount-settles-with-trump-for-16m-over-60-minutes-interview-with-kamala-harris\\\">paid<\\/a> $16m to Trump to settle a defamation lawsuit the president had filed against 60 Minutes, a move that was largely criticized by media watchdogs. Paramount also announced the 2026 <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/tv-and-radio\\/2025\\/jul\\/18\\/the-late-show-with-stephen-colbert-to-end-in-2026-as-cbs-cancels-show\\\">cancellation<\\/a> of Stephen Colbert\\u2019s show, which was widely seen as a capitulation to Trump.<\\/p> <p>Brendan Carr, chairman of the Federal Communications Commissions, which greenlit the merger, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/variety.com\\/2025\\/tv\\/news\\/fcc-brendan-carr-skydance-reform-cbs-1236469119\\/\\\">said<\\/a> that he was \\u201cpleased\\u201d with commitments the company made to reform CBS. In a letter to Carr, Skydance <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.fcc.gov\\/ecfs\\/document\\/1072299913934\\/2\\\">said<\\/a> it would ensure that the new company\\u2019s \\u201carray of news and entertainment programming embodies a diversity of viewpoints across the political and ideological spectrum\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>Paramount Skydance is also reportedly preparing to make a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/2025\\/sep\\/11\\/paramount-skydance-warner-bros-discovery\\\">bid<\\/a> to buy Warner Bros Discovery, the company that owns CNN.<\\/p> <p>On Monday, Ellison suggested the acquisition of the Free Press \\u2013 and Weiss\\u2019s appointment as editor-in-chief \\u2013 would help CBS News to reach \\u201cthe majority of the country\\u201d.<\\/p>\",\"wordcount\":\"718\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-06T12:59:28Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-10-06T15:27:07Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3c478\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/d20eacbe6763e8b3d95f35a3db97ec579b01e189\\/520_0_5200_4160\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"Paramount Skydance has appointed Bari Weiss, a former New York Times opinion writer who launched an \\u201canti-woke\\u201d commentary website, as editor-in-chief of CBS News. Five years after an acrimonious exit from the New York Times, Weiss, 41, has been installed at the top of one of the most venerated institutions in US news \\u2013 solidifying the meteoric rise of a divisive figure in media. She will report directly to David Ellison, the son of the billionaire tech mogul Larry Ellison and head of Paramount Skydance, the company that owns CBS News, which has acquired the Free Press, Weiss\\u2019s media startup. As editor-in-chief, Weiss will probably play a major role in shaping news coverage at the network. Where did Weiss get her start? Weiss held editorial roles at Jewish news outlets early in her career, including Haaretz, the Forward and Tablet. In 2013, she joined the opinion staff at the Wall Street Journal. In 2017, she joined Brett Stephens in moving to the New York Times\\u2019 opinion desk, where she started writing her own column. What did she do at the New York Times? As a journalist at the New York Times, Weiss developed a reputation for both criticizing Donald Trump in his first term and cracking down on the left\\u2019s cancel culture, from cultural appropriation to protests on college campuses. In the swirls of the #MeToo movement, she penned a viral op-ed defending comedian Aziz Ansari, who was accused of sexual misconduct in an anonymous essay. Weiss said at the time that the essay \\u201ctransforms what ought to be a movement for women\\u2019s empowerment into an emblem for female helplessness\\u201d. Why did Weiss leave the Times? Weiss\\u2019s departure from the Times increased her profile even more. In July 2020, she published a public resignation letter, addressed to Times publisher AG Schulzberger, where she accused the company of becoming partisan, and reporting stories \\u201cto satisfy the narrowest of audiences\\u201d. She also said she was \\u201cthe subject of constant bullying by colleagues who disagree with my views\\u201d. The Times said at the time it was committed to \\u201cfostering an environment of honest, searching and empathetic dialogue\\u201d between its employees. What is the Free Press? Months after her departure from the Times, Weiss started a newsletter called Common Sense. The newsletter eventually expanded into a media startup, the Free Press, which publishes newsletters and podcasts. The company received backing from investors including the venture capitalists Marc Andreesen and David Sacks and former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz. At the Free Press, Weiss published controversial reports and series, including the podcast The Witch Trials of JK Rowling, about the Harry Potter author and her clash with liberals over her views on trans people, and a report on the Columbia pro-Palestine encampments with the headline \\u201cCamping Out at Columbia\\u2019s Communist Coachella\\u201d. The author of a book titled How to Fight Anti-Semitism, Weiss is a longtime, staunch supporter of Israel and has utilized the Free Press to defend the country during the war in Gaza. Why is Paramount Skydance acquiring the Free Press? Skydance Media made an agreement with the Trump administration that its content will promote a \\u201cdiversity of viewpoints\\u201d in the company\\u2019s bid to the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to merge with Paramount Global. The FCC agreed to the merger in July, which saw Skydance pay $8bn to merge with Paramount, making Ellison in charge of the new Paramount Skydance company. Ahead of the merger, Paramount Global also paid $16m to Trump to settle a defamation lawsuit the president had filed against 60 Minutes, a move that was largely criticized by media watchdogs. Paramount also announced the 2026 cancellation of Stephen Colbert\\u2019s show, which was widely seen as a capitulation to Trump. Brendan Carr, chairman of the Federal Communications Commissions, which greenlit the merger, said that he was \\u201cpleased\\u201d with commitments the company made to reform CBS. In a letter to Carr, Skydance said it would ensure that the new company\\u2019s \\u201carray of news and entertainment programming embodies a diversity of viewpoints across the political and ideological spectrum\\u201d. Paramount Skydance is also reportedly preparing to make a bid to buy Warner Bros Discovery, the company that owns CNN. On Monday, Ellison suggested the acquisition of the Free Press \\u2013 and Weiss\\u2019s appointment as editor-in-chief \\u2013 would help CBS News to reach \\u201cthe majority of the country\\u201d.\",\"charCount\":\"4457\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/lauren-aratani\\\">Lauren Aratani<\\/a>\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL);
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `author_id`, `category_id`, `external_id`, `title`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `image_url`, `published_at`, `raw`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `source_id`) VALUES
(139, NULL, NULL, 'us-news/2025/oct/15/zohran-mamdani-fox-news-trump', '‘He may be watching’: Mamdani on Fox News speaks directly to Trump', 'New York mayoral contender steps into lion’s den and says he is ‘ready to speak at any time’ to help lower cost of living', 'Zohran Mamdani, the leading candidate to be the next mayor of New York, stepped into the lion’s den on Wednesday when he sat for an interview with Fox News, the rightwing news organization that has spent weeks demonizing him and his democratic socialist goals. Speaking to host Martha MacCallum, Mamdani was asked about funding for his proposals, which include freezing increases on rent-stabilized apartments, providing free buses and offering free childcare – and whether other services would be cut to achieve those goals. “I don’t think we have to cut,” Mamdani said. “I’ve spoken about raising taxes on the wealthiest. And, frankly, this is an issue that we have here in New York City, and, frankly, even across this country.” Mamdani said he had spoken to people who voted for Donald Trump in New York who told him it was the “cost of living” that “drove them to vote” for the president. Mamdani said that, despite that, “what we’re seeing time and time again is we’re more focused on the question of billionaires and the most profitable corporations than we are on people who can’t even afford to make ends meet in the city”. Following his surprise victory over Andrew Cuomo in the Democratic primary, Mamdani has for months led the polls to be New York’s next mayor. A survey released by Quinnipiac last week showed Mamdani winning 46% of the vote to the former New York governor’s 33%. The Republican candidate, Curtis Sliwa, was at 15%. That rise has brought attention from outlets such as Fox News, which has closely covered Mamdani, sometimes publishing multiple news stories on him a day. Jesse Watters, the network’s prime-time host, has been a frequent critic, describing Mamdani as a “communist”, which he is not, and calling him “Kamala Harris with a beard”, while Sean Hannity suggested that the rise of Mamdani, who is Muslim, is evidence that “an extremism is taking root right before your very eyes”. In an interview that rehashed several rightwing critiques of Mamdani, MacCallum suggested he may lack the qualifications for the role. “President Trump said that you never worked a day in your life,” MacCallum told Mamdani, before asking what qualifies him to run the city. In response, Mamdani spoke directly into the camera, alluding to how the outgoing mayor, Eric Adams, bowed to pressure from the Trump administration to cooperate on immigration crackdowns – before the Trump-led justice department dropped a federal corruption case against him. “I want to take this moment, because you spoke about President Trump, and he may be watching right now, and I just want to speak directly to the president,” Mamdani said. “I will not be a mayor like Mayor [Eric] Adams, who will call you to figure out how to stay out of jail. I won’t be a disgraced governor like Andrew Cuomo, who will call you to ask how to win this election. I can do those things on my own. I will, however, be a mayor who is ready to speak at any time to lower the cost of living. “That’s the way that I’m going to lead this city. That’s the partnership I want to build, not only with Washington DC, but [with] anyone across this country.” The interview came as Mamdani prepared for a debate with Cuomo and Sliwa on Thursday night. Adams suspended his re-election campaign in late September. Cuomo, who has centered his campaign on reducing crime, will likely seek to contrast his decades of experience in politics with Mamdani’s newcomer status. The former governor, who resigned in 2021 after he was accused of sexual harassment by multiple women, has run numerous ads attacking Mamdani. The issue of the Israel-Hamas peace deal is likely to come up, given Cuomo’s strong support for Israel and Mamdani’s opposing stance. Mamdani has criticized Israel’s war in Gaza and called the bombing of the territory a “genocide”. Mamdani was asked questions about the region on Wednesday, including whether he would give credit to Trump for the fledgling deal. Mamdani, stressing that his focus would be on New York rather than international politics, said he was thankful for the ceasefire, adding: “I have hope that it will actually endure and that it will be lasting.” “I think it’s too early to [give credit],” Mamdani said. “But if it proves to be something that is lasting, something that is durable, then I think that that’s where you give credit.” This article was amended on 16 October 2025 to clarify that the recent Quinnipiac poll showed Curtis Sliwa at 15%, not 22%, as we originally said.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/oct/15/zohran-mamdani-fox-news-trump', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/048ef463f5187da0964930616cd4832d5f9a78e5/213_0_3052_2441/500.jpg', '2025-10-16 04:12:45', '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/15\\/zohran-mamdani-fox-news-trump\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-15T21:12:45Z\",\"webTitle\":\"\\u2018He may be watching\\u2019: Mamdani on Fox News speaks directly to Trump\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/15\\/zohran-mamdani-fox-news-trump\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/15\\/zohran-mamdani-fox-news-trump\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"\\u2018He may be watching\\u2019: Mamdani on Fox News speaks directly to Trump\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>New York mayoral contender steps into lion\\u2019s den and says he is \\u2018ready to speak at any time\\u2019 to help lower cost of living<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"New York mayoral contender steps into lion\\u2019s den and says he is \\u2018ready to speak at any time\\u2019 to help lower cost of living\",\"byline\":\"Adam Gabbatt\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"0