emocratic primary, Mamdani has for months led the polls to be New York\\u2019s next mayor. A survey released <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/poll.qu.edu\\/poll-release?releaseid=3935\\\">by Quinnipiac<\\/a> last week showed Mamdani winning 46% of the vote to the former New York governor\\u2019s 33%. The Republican candidate, Curtis Sliwa, was at 15%.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/ng-interactive\\/2025\\/oct\\/14\\/curtis-sliwa-nyc-republican-mayoral-candidate\\\">Republican in New York\\u2019s mayor race: eccentric street vigilante who could secure Mamdani\\u2019s win<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>That rise has brought attention from outlets such as Fox News, which has closely covered Mamdani, sometimes publishing multiple news stories on him a day. Jesse Watters, the network\\u2019s prime-time host, has been <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.facebook.com\\/watch\\/?v=831710982763736\\\">a frequent critic<\\/a>, describing Mamdani as a \\u201ccommunist\\u201d, which he is not, and calling him \\u201cKamala Harris with a beard\\u201d, while Sean Hannity suggested that the rise of Mamdani, who is Muslim, is evidence that \\u201can extremism is taking root right before your very eyes\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>In an interview that rehashed several rightwing critiques of Mamdani, MacCallum suggested he may lack the qualifications for the role. \\u201cPresident Trump said that you never worked a day in your life,\\u201d MacCallum told Mamdani, before asking what qualifies him to run the city.<\\/p> <p>In response, Mamdani spoke directly into the camera, alluding to how the outgoing mayor, Eric Adams, bowed to pressure from the Trump administration to cooperate on immigration crackdowns \\u2013 before the Trump-led justice department dropped a federal corruption case against him.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cI want to take this moment, because you spoke about President Trump, and he may be watching right now, and I just want to speak directly to the president,\\u201d Mamdani said.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cI will not be a mayor like Mayor [Eric] Adams, who will call you to figure out how to stay out of jail. I won\\u2019t be a disgraced governor like Andrew Cuomo, who will call you to ask how to win this election. I can do those things on my own. I will, however, be a mayor who is ready to speak at any time to lower the cost of living.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cThat\\u2019s the way that I\\u2019m going to lead this city. That\\u2019s the partnership I want to build, not only with Washington DC, but [with] anyone across this country.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>The interview came as Mamdani prepared for a debate with Cuomo and Sliwa on Thursday night. Adams suspended his re-election campaign in late September.<\\/p> <p>Cuomo, who has centered his campaign on reducing crime, will likely seek to contrast his decades of experience in politics with Mamdani\\u2019s newcomer status. The former governor, who resigned in 2021 after he was accused of sexual harassment by multiple women, has run numerous ads attacking Mamdani.<\\/p> <p>The issue of the Israel-Hamas peace deal is likely to come up, given Cuomo\\u2019s strong support for Israel and Mamdani\\u2019s opposing stance. Mamdani has criticized Israel\\u2019s war in Gaza and called the bombing of the territory a \\u201cgenocide\\u201d. Mamdani was asked questions about the region on Wednesday, including whether he would give credit to Trump for the fledgling deal.<\\/p> <p>Mamdani, stressing that his focus would be on New York rather than international politics, said he was thankful for the ceasefire, adding: \\u201cI have hope that it will actually endure and that it will be lasting.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>\\u201cI think it\\u2019s too early to [give credit],\\u201d Mamdani said. \\u201cBut if it proves to be something that is lasting, something that is durable, then I think that that\\u2019s where you give credit.\\u201d<\\/p> <ul> <li>