ho can\\u2019t even afford to make ends meet in the city\\u201d. Following his surprise victory over Andrew Cuomo in the Democratic primary, Mamdani has for months led the polls to be New York\\u2019s next mayor. A survey released by Quinnipiac last week showed Mamdani winning 46% of the vote to the former New York governor\\u2019s 33%. The Republican candidate, Curtis Sliwa, was at 15%. That rise has brought attention from outlets such as Fox News, which has closely covered Mamdani, sometimes publishing multiple news stories on him a day. Jesse Watters, the network\\u2019s prime-time host, has been a frequent critic, describing Mamdani as a \\u201ccommunist\\u201d, which he is not, and calling him \\u201cKamala Harris with a beard\\u201d, while Sean Hannity suggested that the rise of Mamdani, who is Muslim, is evidence that \\u201can extremism is taking root right before your very eyes\\u201d. In an interview that rehashed several rightwing critiques of Mamdani, MacCallum suggested he may lack the qualifications for the role. \\u201cPresident Trump said that you never worked a day in your life,\\u201d MacCallum told Mamdani, before asking what qualifies him to run the city. In response, Mamdani spoke directly into the camera, alluding to how the outgoing mayor, Eric Adams, bowed to pressure from the Trump administration to cooperate on immigration crackdowns \\u2013 before the Trump-led justice department dropped a federal corruption case against him. \\u201cI want to take this moment, because you spoke about President Trump, and he may be watching right now, and I just want to speak directly to the president,\\u201d Mamdani said. \\u201cI will not be a mayor like Mayor [Eric] Adams, who will call you to figure out how to stay out of jail. I won\\u2019t be a disgraced governor like Andrew Cuomo, who will call you to ask how to win this election. I can do those things on my own. I will, however, be a mayor who is ready to speak at any time to lower the cost of living. \\u201cThat\\u2019s the way that I\\u2019m going to lead this city. That\\u2019s the partnership I want to build, not only with Washington DC, but [with] anyone across this country.\\u201d The interview came as Mamdani prepared for a debate with Cuomo and Sliwa on Thursday night. Adams suspended his re-election campaign in late September. Cuomo, who has centered his campaign on reducing crime, will likely seek to contrast his decades of experience in politics with Mamdani\\u2019s newcomer status. The former governor, who resigned in 2021 after he was accused of sexual harassment by multiple women, has run numerous ads attacking Mamdani. The issue of the Israel-Hamas peace deal is likely to come up, given Cuomo\\u2019s strong support for Israel and Mamdani\\u2019s opposing stance. Mamdani has criticized Israel\\u2019s war in Gaza and called the bombing of the territory a \\u201cgenocide\\u201d. Mamdani was asked questions about the region on Wednesday, including whether he would give credit to Trump for the fledgling deal. Mamdani, stressing that his focus would be on New York rather than international politics, said he was thankful for the ceasefire, adding: \\u201cI have hope that it will actually endure and that it will be lasting.\\u201d \\u201cI think it\\u2019s too early to [give credit],\\u201d Mamdani said. \\u201cBut if it proves to be something that is lasting, something that is durable, then I think that that\\u2019s where you give credit.\\u201d This article was amended on 16 October 2025 to clarify that the recent Quinnipiac poll showed Curtis Sliwa at 15%, not 22%, as we originally said.\",\"charCount\":\"4488\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/adam-gabbatt\\\">Adam Gabbatt<\\/a>\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL),
(140, NULL, NULL, 'business/2025/sep/12/uk-economy-flatlines-july-grim-news-rachel-reeves', 'UK economy flatlines in July in grim news for Rachel Reeves', 'Official GDP figures confirm widely expected slowdown after strong expansion in first half of the year', 'The UK economy flatlined in July, according to official figures, in grim news for Rachel Reeves as she gears up for a challenging budget. It was a slowdown compared with June, when the economy grew by 0.4%, according to the Office for National Statistics. GDP expanded strongly in the first half of the year, making the UK the fastest-growing economy in the G7, but it had been widely expected to slow in the second half. The ONS said that growth in the services and construction sectors in July was offset by a 0.9% fall in the production sector, which includes manufacturing. The downbeat data will raise questions about Labour’s promise to kickstart the economy. A Treasury spokesperson said: “We know there’s more to do to boost growth, because, whilst our economy isn’t broken, it does feel stuck. That’s the result of years of underinvestment, which we’re determined to reverse through our plan for change.” The ONS said that GDP grew by 0.2% in the three months to July, compared with the three months to April, down from 0.3% in the three months to June. Statisticians see three-month figures as a better guide to the underlying health of the economy than one-month data, which tends to be more volatile. The ONS director of economic statistics, Liz McKeown, said: “Growth in the economy as a whole continued to slow over the last three months. While services growth held up, production fell back further. “Within services, health, computer programming and office support services all performed well, while the falls in production were driven by broad-based weakness across manufacturing industries.” The pound weakened after the news, to trade 0.2% lower at $1.355 against the US dollar by mid-morning in London. Business groups have blamed Reeves’s £25bn increase in employer national insurance contribution, which came into force in April alongside a significant rise in the national living wage, for constraining growth. The British Chambers of Commerce (BCC) responded to the data by warning Reeves against levying more taxes on business. Stuart Morrison, the BCC’s research manager, said: “The business landscape remains challenging, particularly for SMEs [small and medium-size enterprises], with cost pressures impacting investment, recruitment and trade. “The government has acknowledged it has asked a lot of business in the past year. Our message is now clear – there must be no more taxes on business in the autumn budget.” The chancellor is widely expected to have to present a package of tax increases when she delivers her second budget on 26 November, to compensate for an anticipated downgrade in the Office for Budget Responsibility’s forecasts. However, after the news of zero growth in July, economists warned that speculation about tax increases was likely to continue weighing on confidence. Fergus Jimenez-England, an associate economist at the National Institute of Economic and Social Research, said: “Economic activity in the third quarter will be constrained by fiscal uncertainty weighing on household and business sentiments. Growth at this pace will do little to ease the fiscal challenges confronting the chancellor this autumn.” Daisy Cooper, the Liberal Democrats’ Treasury spokesperson, said: “The government talks of going full-throttle on growth but the reality is they have left the handbrake on. “Their growth-crushing jobs tax risks hollowing out our high streets and ministers’ refusal to jettison their shortsighted red lines on cutting red tape with Europe is holding back our exporters.” Trade data published alongside the GDP update showed the UK’s goods deficit widening by £3bn in the three months to July, to £61.9bn. The ONS said exports to the US rose by £800m in July but had not returned to the levels seen before Donald Trump’s tariffs were imposed. The slowdown in economic growth comes alongside higher-than-expected inflation, which jumped to 3.8% in July, prompting investors to rein in expectations of further interest rate cuts from the Bank of England in the coming months. The Bank’s nine-member monetary policy committee is expected to leave rates on hold at 4% when it meets next Thursday. Jobs and inflation data, due to be published earlier in the week, will give more detail of the state of the economy – though policymakers have repeatedly warned that known flaws in ONS data are making it difficult to get a clear picture.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/business/2025/sep/12/uk-economy-flatlines-july-grim-news-rachel-reeves', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/fbcea043041927ca6bb2133abc7876a8cf09e8fd/1163_1314_5187_4150/500.jpg', '2025-09-12 16:20:02', '{\"id\":\"business\\/2025\\/sep\\/12\\/uk-economy-flatlines-july-grim-news-rachel-reeves\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"business\",\"sectionName\":\"Business\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-09-12T09:20:02Z\",\"webTitle\":\"UK economy flatlines in July in grim news for Rachel Reeves\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/2025\\/sep\\/12\\/uk-economy-flatlines-july-grim-news-rachel-reeves\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/business\\/2025\\/sep\\/12\\/uk-economy-flatlines-july-grim-news-rachel-reeves\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"UK economy flatlines in July in grim news for Rachel Reeves\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Official GDP figures confirm widely expected slowdown after strong expansion in first half of the year<\\/p><ul><li><p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/live\\/2025\\/sep\\/12\\/uk-gdp-report-economy-july-tariffs-inflation-consumer-confidence-business-live\\\">Business live \\u2013 updates throughout the day<\\/a><\\/p><\\/li><\\/ul>\",\"trailText\":\"Official GDP figures confirm widely expected slowdown after strong expansion in first half of the year\",\"byline\":\"Heather Stewart\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"fbcea043041927ca6bb2133abc7876a8cf09e8fd\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/fbcea043041927ca6bb2133abc7876a8cf09e8fd\\/1163_1314_5187_4150\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"A woman paints a pattern on a ceramic plate\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">GDP had been widely expected to slow in the second half of the year.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Christopher Thomond\\/The Guardian<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>The UK economy flatlined in July, according to official figures, in grim news for Rachel Reeves as she gears up for a challenging budget.<\\/p> <p>It was a slowdown compared with June, when the economy grew by 0.4%, according to the Office for National Statistics.<\\/p> <p>GDP expanded strongly in the first half of the year, making the UK the fastest-growing economy in the G7, but it had been widely expected to slow in the second half.<\\/p> <p>The ONS said that growth in the services and construction sectors in July was offset by a 0.9% fall in the production sector, which includes manufacturing.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/2025\\/sep\\/09\\/cbi-boss-calls-for-rachel-reeves-to-tear-up-labours-manifesto-pledge-on-tax\\\">CBI boss calls for Reeves to tear up Labour\\u2019s pledge not to raise tax<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>The downbeat data will raise questions about Labour\\u2019s promise to kickstart the economy.<\\/p> <p>A Treasury spokesperson said: \\u201cWe know there\\u2019s more to do to boost growth, because, whilst our economy isn\\u2019t broken, it does feel stuck. That\\u2019s the result of years of underinvestment, which we\\u2019re determined to reverse through our plan for change.\\u201d<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-interactive interactive\\\" data-interactive=\\\"https:\\/\\/interactive.guim.co.uk\\/embed\\/iframe-wrapper\\/0.1\\/boot.js\\\" data-canonical-url=\\\"https:\\/\\/interactive.guim.co.uk\\/datawrapper\\/embed\\/g4LXt\\/1\\/\\\" data-alt=\\\"a bar graph showing monthly growth and declines in gross domestic product\\\"> <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/interactive.guim.co.uk\\/datawrapper\\/embed\\/g4LXt\\/1\\/\\\">Interactive<\\/a> <\\/figure>  <p>The ONS said that GDP grew by 0.2% in the three months to July, compared with the three months to April, down from 0.3% in the three months to June. Statisticians see three-month figures as a better guide to the underlying health of the economy than one-month data, which tends to be more volatile.<\\/p> <p>The ONS director of economic statistics, Liz McKeown, said: \\u201cGrowth in the economy as a whole continued to slow over the last three months. While services growth held up, production fell back further.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cWithin services, health, computer programming and office support services all performed well, while the falls in production were driven by broad-based weakness across manufacturing industries.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>The pound weakened after the news, to trade 0.2% lower at $1.355 against the US dollar by mid-morning in London.<\\/p> <p>Business groups have blamed Reeves\\u2019s <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/uk-news\\/2024\\/oct\\/30\\/autumn-budget-2024-rachel-reeves-tax-rises-public-services\\\">\\u00a325bn increase in employer national insurance contribution<\\/a>, which came into force in April alongside a significant rise in the national living wage, for constraining growth.<\\/p> <p>The British Chambers of Commerce (BCC) responded to the data by warning Reeves against levying more taxes on business.<\\/p> <p>Stuart Morrison, the BCC\\u2019s research manager, said: \\u201cThe business landscape remains challenging, particularly for SMEs [small and medium-size enterprises], with cost pressures impacting investment, recruitment and trade.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cThe government has acknowledged it has asked a lot of business in the past year. Our message is now clear \\u2013 there must be no more taxes on business in the autumn budget.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>The chancellor is widely expected to have to present a package of tax increases when she delivers her second budget on 26 November, to compensate for an anticipated downgrade in the Office for Budget Responsibility\\u2019s forecasts.<\\/p> <p>However, after the news of zero growth in July, economists warned that speculation about tax increases was likely to continue weighing on confidence.<\\/p> <p>Fergus Jimenez-England, an associate economist at the National Institute of Economic and Social Research, said: \\u201cEconomic activity in the third quarter will be constrained by fiscal uncertainty weighing on household and business sentiments. Growth at this pace will do little to ease the fiscal challenges confronting the chancellor this autumn.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>Daisy Cooper, the Liberal Democrats\\u2019 Treasury spokesperson, said: \\u201cThe government talks of going full-throttle on growth but the reality is they have left the handbrake on.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cTheir growth-crushing jobs tax risks hollowing out our high streets and ministers\\u2019 refusal to jettison their shortsighted red lines on cutting red tape with Europe is holding back our exporters.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>Trade data published alongside the GDP update showed the UK\\u2019s goods deficit widening by \\u00a33bn in the three months to July, to \\u00a361.9bn. The ONS said exports to the US rose by \\u00a3800m in July but had not returned to the levels seen before Donald Trump\\u2019s tariffs were imposed.<\\/p> <p>The slowdown in economic growth comes alongside higher-than-expected inflation, which <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/2025\\/aug\\/20\\/inflation-rises-july-pause-interest-rate-cuts\\\">jumped to 3.8% in July<\\/a>, prompting investors to rein in expectations of further interest rate cuts from the Bank of England in the coming months.<\\/p> <p>The Bank\\u2019s nine-member monetary policy committee is expected to leave rates on hold at 4% when it meets next Thursday.<\\/p> <p>Jobs and inflation data, due to be published earlier in the week, will give more detail of the state of the economy \\u2013 though policymakers have repeatedly warned that known flaws in ONS data are making it difficult to get a clear picture.<\\/p>\",\"newspaperPageNumber\":\"45\",\"wordcount\":\"710\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-09-12T06:04:18Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-09-12T17:44:08Z\",\"newspaperEditionDate\":\"2025-09-13T00:00:00Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"UK\",\"publication\":\"The Guardian\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x37c8e\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/fbcea043041927ca6bb2133abc7876a8cf09e8fd\\/1163_1314_5187_4150\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"The UK economy flatlined in July, according to official figures, in grim news for Rachel Reeves as she gears up for a challenging budget. It was a slowdown compared with June, when the economy grew by 0.4%, according to the Office for National Statistics. GDP expanded strongly in the first half of the year, making the UK the fastest-growing economy in the G7, but it had been widely expected to slow in the second half. The ONS said that growth in the services and construction sectors in July was offset by a 0.9% fall in the production sector, which includes manufacturing. The downbeat data will raise questions about Labour\\u2019s promise to kickstart the economy. A Treasury spokesperson said: \\u201cWe know there\\u2019s more to do to boost growth, because, whilst our economy isn\\u2019t broken, it does feel stuck. That\\u2019s the result of years of underinvestment, which we\\u2019re determined to reverse through our plan for change.\\u201d The ONS said that GDP grew by 0.2% in the three months to July, compared with the three months to April, down from 0.3% in the three months to June. Statisticians see three-month figures as a better guide to the underlying health of the economy than one-month data, which tends to be more volatile. The ONS director of economic statistics, Liz McKeown, said: \\u201cGrowth in the economy as a whole continued to slow over the last three months. While services growth held up, production fell back further. \\u201cWithin services, health, computer programming and office support services all performed well, while the falls in production were driven by broad-based weakness across manufacturing industries.\\u201d The pound weakened after the news, to trade 0.2% lower at $1.355 against the US dollar by mid-morning in London. Business groups have blamed Reeves\\u2019s \\u00a325bn increase in employer national insurance contribution, which came into force in April alongside a significant rise in the national living wage, for constraining growth. The British Chambers of Commerce (BCC) responded to the data by warning Reeves against levying more taxes on business. Stuart Morrison, the BCC\\u2019s research manager, said: \\u201cThe business landscape remains challenging, particularly for SMEs [small and medium-size enterprises], with cost pressures impacting investment, recruitment and trade. \\u201cThe government has acknowledged it has asked a lot of business in the past year. Our message is now clear \\u2013 there must be no more taxes on business in the autumn budget.\\u201d The chancellor is widely expected to have to present a package of tax increases when she delivers her second budget on 26 November, to compensate for an anticipated downgrade in the Office for Budget Responsibility\\u2019s forecasts. However, after the news of zero growth in July, economists warned that speculation about tax increases was likely to continue weighing on confidence. Fergus Jimenez-England, an associate economist at the National Institute of Economic and Social Research, said: \\u201cEconomic activity in the third quarter will be constrained by fiscal uncertainty weighing on household and business sentiments. Growth at this pace will do little to ease the fiscal challenges confronting the chancellor this autumn.\\u201d Daisy Cooper, the Liberal Democrats\\u2019 Treasury spokesperson, said: \\u201cThe government talks of going full-throttle on growth but the reality is they have left the handbrake on. \\u201cTheir growth-crushing jobs tax risks hollowing out our high streets and ministers\\u2019 refusal to jettison their shortsighted red lines on cutting red tape with Europe is holding back our exporters.\\u201d Trade data published alongside the GDP update showed the UK\\u2019s goods deficit widening by \\u00a33bn in the three months to July, to \\u00a361.9bn. The ONS said exports to the US rose by \\u00a3800m in July but had not returned to the levels seen before Donald Trump\\u2019s tariffs were imposed. The slowdown in economic growth comes alongside higher-than-expected inflation, which jumped to 3.8% in July, prompting investors to rein in expectations of further interest rate cuts from the Bank of England in the coming months. The Bank\\u2019s nine-member monetary policy committee is expected to leave rates on hold at 4% when it meets next Thursday. Jobs and inflation data, due to be published earlier in the week, will give more detail of the state of the economy \\u2013 though policymakers have repeatedly warned that known flaws in ONS data are making it difficult to get a clear picture.\",\"charCount\":\"4397\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/heatherstewart\\\">Heather Stewart<\\/a>\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL);
