(143, NULL, NULL, 'media/2025/oct/31/bari-weiss-host-cbs-evening-news', 'Who will Bari Weiss pick as the next anchor of CBS Evening News?', 'With John Dickerson heading out and show’s ratings struggling, new CBS editor-in-chief is looking at several anchors at rival networks', 'For more than half a century, CBS Evening News has been synonymous with the network’s reputation for journalistic excellence, with anchors such as Walter Cronkite and Dan Rather holding court on a nightly basis. Now, it will be up to Bari Weiss, CBS News’s editor in chief, who has no previous background in television, to help decide what comes next for the show, which has struggled to attract viewers. On Monday, CBS Evening News co-anchor John Dickerson – one of the network’s best-known personalities – announced he would leave the network at the end of the year, leaving behind his fellow anchor, Maurice DuBois. While the network has not addressed DuBois’ fate, network insiders expect that CBS News will return to a single anchor format. The question now is whether Weiss and Tom Cibrowski, the network president, will choose an internal candidate, or hire from the outside, as they put their imprint on a ratings-challenged show that, like its rivals, is struggling with the challenges of the digital age. Network management had attempted to shake things up by introducing a new format for the show in January. In addition to having co-anchors, the show pivoted to a formula that prioritized longer, more deeply reported stories rather than hard news run-downs from Washington. Rather than jolting the show out of its long-time position in third place, trailing both ABC World News Tonight and the NBC Nightly News in viewers, the audience dropped off even further. If the network chooses to promote from within, Tony Dokoupil, the morning show co-anchor, stands as good a chance as anyone. Norah O’Donnell, who anchored the show from 2019 to 2024, has also been mentioned. But Weiss seems interested in hiring an external candidate and has shown interest in several top anchors. The problem is that many of them are already under contract at their existing networks for several more years. Bret Baier, the Fox News anchor, is one of those external options, but the evening news anchor made clear this week that he is signed with Fox through 2028. Another candidate, Anderson Cooper, the CNN anchor, is also under contract at the network – though he has a pre-existing relationship with CBS News through his role as a correspondent on 60 Minutes. Weiss has also expressed interest in another Fox anchor, Dana Perino, the Guardian has learned. But Perino, like Baier, is under contract for several more years – into the next decade, in her case – and cannot sign with a rival network. Perino appeared on Weiss’s Honesty with Bari Weiss podcast in May, and the two were effusive in praising each other. “The private Dana is even more gracious and shining than the public one,” Weiss said. “You are a person who models, frankly, just classy behavior, the kind of class that I think a lot of people have forgotten.” Perino described herself as “a huge fan” of Weiss and her wife, Nellie Bowles, and said that their website the Free Press is “one of the best things that has kept me more informed and smarter, and also super entertained”. In chatter among employees, another name that has come up – but isn’t likely in serious consideration – is Shepard Smith, a former Fox News anchor, who resigned suddenly from the network in 2019. He signed with financial network CNBC to anchor a nightly newscast, but the experiment failed and he left the network in 2022. Since then, Smith has kept a low profile. Even if Weiss can land a big-name outsider, it’s an open question whether it would actually make a difference. CBS News has gone through a host of evening news anchors – since 2011, the show has been hosted by Katie Couric, Scott Pelley, Anthony Mason, Jeff Glor and O’Donnell, in addition to the current pairing – but none have been able to change the evening news pecking order. And with every switch behind the anchor desk, “you have sent viewers away each time”, said a former CBS News executive who requested anonymity to speak candidly. Generally, viewers tend to stick with their evening news show of choice and seem unwilling to try out the competition. While NBC recently had a change in the anchor chair, with Tom Llamas replacing longtime anchor Lester Holt, ABC has seen continuity with David Muir leading the show since 2014. This season, Muir’s show has averaged 7.5 million viewers, comfortably ahead of NBC (5.7 million viewers) and far ahead of CBS (3.7 million viewers). “She’s got a disaster on her hands at the Evening News and she’s got to fix the Evening News, and that’s got to be her new project,” said Tom Bettag, a lecturer at the University of Maryland’s journalism school who spent 22 years at CBS News, including a five-year stint as executive producer of the nightly show under Dan Rather. While the show’s ratings aren’t what they were, Bettag said the show is still essential to the identity of the network, not to mention a reliable source of advertiser revenue. “If they have a really strong Evening News, it lifts the whole place,” he added. CBS News employees – who were not authorized to comment – were less specific about what needs to change on the evening show and who the network should pick to anchor. “What they need is someone who plays a very good anchor man and hopefully has journalistic chops and a very talented show-runner,” one staffer told the Guardian, while another was more concise: “We need to just do a damn newscast. Don’t overthink it.” The CBS Evening News may not hold the place in society it once did, but what Weiss (and Cibrowski) decide to do with the show could hint at her longterm strategy and provide an early signal of whether she might be successful in turning around the network’s fortunes. “I wouldn’t say it’s the most important decision, but it’s probably the most telling decision, about where she’s taking the direction of the company,” the former CBS News executive said.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/media/2025/oct/31/bari-weiss-host-cbs-evening-news', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/efe609a8c42a1aaf28063f445eda1be8ccb19436/1_0_4998_4000/500.jpg', '2025-10-31 17:00:22', '{\"id\":\"media\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/bari-weiss-host-cbs-evening-news\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"media\",\"sectionName\":\"Media\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-31T10:00:22Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Who will Bari Weiss pick as the next anchor of CBS Evening News?\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/bari-weiss-host-cbs-evening-news\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/bari-weiss-host-cbs-evening-news\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Who will Bari Weiss pick as the next anchor of CBS Evening News?\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>With John Dickerson heading out and show\\u2019s ratings struggling, new CBS editor-in-chief is looking at several anchors at rival networks<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"With John Dickerson heading out and show\\u2019s ratings struggling, new CBS editor-in-chief is looking at several anchors at rival networks\",\"byline\":\"Jeremy Barr in Washington\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"efe609a8c42a1aaf28063f445eda1be8ccb19436\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/efe609a8c42a1aaf28063f445eda1be8ccb19436\\/1_0_4998_4000\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"A composite image of a woman speaking into a mic and a man seated behind a desk.\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">Bari Weiss and John Dickerson.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Composite: Gail Schulman\\/  Francine Orr<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>For more than half a century, CBS Evening News has been synonymous with the network\\u2019s reputation for journalistic excellence, with anchors such as Walter Cronkite and Dan Rather holding court on a nightly basis. Now, it will be up to Bari Weiss, CBS News\\u2019s editor in chief, who has no previous background in television, to help decide what comes next for the show, which has struggled to attract viewers.<\\/p> <p>On Monday, CBS Evening News co-anchor John Dickerson \\u2013 one of the network\\u2019s best-known personalities \\u2013 <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/27\\/cbs-evening-news-anchor-john-dickerson-resigns\\\">announced he would leave the network<\\/a> at the end of the year, leaving behind his fellow anchor, Maurice DuBois.<\\/p> <p>While the network has not addressed DuBois\\u2019 fate, network insiders expect that CBS News will return to a single anchor format. The question now is whether Weiss and Tom Cibrowski, the network president, will choose an internal candidate, or hire from the outside, as they put their imprint on a ratings-challenged show that, like its rivals, is struggling with the challenges of the digital age.<\\/p> <p>Network management had attempted to shake things up by introducing a new format for the show in January. In addition to having co-anchors, the show pivoted to a formula that prioritized longer, more deeply reported stories rather than hard news run-downs from Washington. Rather than jolting the show out of its long-time position in third place, trailing both ABC World News Tonight and the NBC Nightly News in viewers, the audience dropped off even further.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/2025\\/oct\\/29\\/cbs-news-layoffs-paramount\\\">CBS News staffers lose jobs in \\u2018bloodbath\\u2019 as part of sweeping cuts from Paramount<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>If the network chooses to promote from within, Tony Dokoupil, the morning show co-anchor, stands as good a chance as anyone. Norah O\\u2019Donnell, who anchored the show from 2019 to 2024, has also been mentioned.<\\/p> <p>But Weiss seems interested in hiring an external candidate and has shown interest in several top anchors. The problem is that many of them are already under contract at their existing networks for several more years.<\\/p> <p>Bret Baier, the Fox News anchor, is one of those external options, but the evening news anchor made clear this week that he is signed with Fox through 2028. Another candidate, Anderson Cooper, the CNN anchor, is also under contract at the network \\u2013 though he has a pre-existing relationship with CBS News through his role as a correspondent on 60 Minutes.<\\/p> <p>Weiss has also expressed interest in another Fox anchor, Dana Perino, the Guardian has learned. But Perino, like Baier, is under contract for several more years \\u2013 into the next decade, in her case \\u2013 and cannot sign with a rival network.<\\/p> <p>Perino appeared on Weiss\\u2019s Honesty with Bari Weiss podcast in May, and the two were effusive in praising each other. \\u201cThe private Dana is even more gracious and shining than the public one,\\u201d Weiss said. \\u201cYou are a person who models, frankly, just classy behavior, the kind of class that I think a lot of people have forgotten.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>Perino described herself as \\u201ca huge fan\\u201d of Weiss and her wife, Nellie Bowles, and said that their website the Free Press is \\u201cone of the best things that has kept me more informed and smarter, and also super entertained\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>In chatter among employees, another name that has come up \\u2013 but isn\\u2019t likely in serious consideration \\u2013 is Shepard Smith, a former Fox News anchor, who resigned suddenly from the network in 2019. He signed with financial network CNBC to anchor a nightly newscast, but the experiment failed and he left the network in 2022. Since then, Smith has kept a low profile.<\\/p> <aside class=\\\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\\\"> <p> <span>Related: <\\/span><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/commentisfree\\/2025\\/oct\\/29\\/cbs-tiktok-us-media-donald-trump-allies-democracy\\\">From CBS to TikTok, US media are falling to Trump\\u2019s allies. This is how democracy crumbles | Owen Jones<\\/a> <\\/p> <\\/aside>  <p>Even if Weiss can land a big-name outsider, it\\u2019s an open question whether it would actually make a difference. CBS News has gone through a host of evening news anchors \\u2013 since 2011, the show has been hosted by Katie Couric, Scott Pelley, Anthony Mason, Jeff Glor and O\\u2019Donnell, in addition to the current pairing \\u2013 but none have been able to change the evening news pecking order. And with every switch behind the anchor desk, \\u201cyou have sent viewers away each time\\u201d, said a former CBS News executive who requested anonymity to speak candidly.<\\/p> <p>Generally, viewers tend to stick with their evening news show of choice and seem unwilling to try out the competition. While NBC recently had a change in the anchor chair, with Tom Llamas replacing longtime anchor Lester Holt, ABC has seen continuity with David Muir leading the show since 2014. This season, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.detpress.com\\/abcnews\\/pressrelease\\/abc-world-news-tonight-with-david-muir-leads-nbc-by-2-million-viewers-biggest-margin-in-14-months\\/\\\">Muir\\u2019s show has averaged 7.5 million viewers<\\/a>, comfortably ahead of NBC (5.7 million viewers) and far ahead of CBS (3.7 million viewers).<\\/p> <p>\\u201cShe\\u2019s got a disaster on her hands at the Evening News and she\\u2019s got to fix the Evening News, and that\\u2019s got to be her new project,\\u201d said Tom Bettag, a lecturer at the University of Maryland\\u2019s journalism school who spent 22 years at CBS News, including a five-year stint as executive producer of the nightly show under Dan Rather.<\\/p> <p>While the show\\u2019s ratings aren\\u2019t what they were, Bettag said the show is still essential to the identity of the network, not to mention a reliable source of advertiser revenue. \\u201cIf they have a really strong Evening News, it lifts the whole place,\\u201d he added.<\\/p> <p>CBS News employees \\u2013 who were not authorized to comment \\u2013 were less specific about what needs to change on the evening show and who the network should pick to anchor. \\u201cWhat they need is someone who plays a very good anchor man and hopefully has journalistic chops and a very talented show-runner,\\u201d one staffer told the Guardian, while another was more concise: \\u201cWe need to just do a damn newscast. Don\\u2019t overthink it.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>The CBS Evening News may not hold the place in society it once did, but what Weiss (and Cibrowski) decide to do with the show could hint at her longterm strategy and provide an early signal of whether she might be successful in turning around the network\\u2019s fortunes.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cI wouldn\\u2019t say it\\u2019s the most important decision, but it\\u2019s probably the most telling decision, about where she\\u2019s taking the direction of the company,\\u201d the former CBS News executive said.<\\/p>\",\"wordcount\":\"1003\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-31T10:00:22Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-10-31T14:04:55Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3hmd4\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/efe609a8c42a1aaf28063f445eda1be8ccb19436\\/1_0_4998_4000\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"For more than half a century, CBS Evening News has been synonymous with the network\\u2019s reputation for journalistic excellence, with anchors such as Walter Cronkite and Dan Rather holding court on a nightly basis. Now, it will be up to Bari Weiss, CBS News\\u2019s editor in chief, who has no previous background in television, to help decide what comes next for the show, which has struggled to attract viewers. On Monday, CBS Evening News co-anchor John Dickerson \\u2013 one of the network\\u2019s best-known personalities \\u2013 announced he would leave the network at the end of the year, leaving behind his fellow anchor, Maurice DuBois. While the network has not addressed DuBois\\u2019 fate, network insiders expect that CBS News will return to a single anchor format. The question now is whether Weiss and Tom Cibrowski, the network president, will choose an internal candidate, or hire from the outside, as they put their imprint on a ratings-challenged show that, like its rivals, is struggling with the challenges of the digital age. Network management had attempted to shake things up by introducing a new format for the show in January. In addition to having co-anchors, the show pivoted to a formula that prioritized longer, more deeply reported stories rather than hard news run-downs from Washington. Rather than jolting the show out of its long-time position in third place, trailing both ABC World News Tonight and the NBC Nightly News in viewers, the audience dropped off even further. If the network chooses to promote from within, Tony Dokoupil, the morning show co-anchor, stands as good a chance as anyone. Norah O\\u2019Donnell, who anchored the show from 2019 to 2024, has also been mentioned. But Weiss seems interested in hiring an external candidate and has shown interest in several top anchors. The problem is that many of them are already under contract at their existing networks for several more years. Bret Baier, the Fox News anchor, is one of those external options, but the evening news anchor made clear this week that he is signed with Fox through 2028. Another candidate, Anderson Cooper, the CNN anchor, is also under contract at the network \\u2013 though he has a pre-existing relationship with CBS News through his role as a correspondent on 60 Minutes. Weiss has also expressed interest in another Fox anchor, Dana Perino, the Guardian has learned. But Perino, like Baier, is under contract for several more years \\u2013 into the next decade, in her case \\u2013 and cannot sign with a rival network. Perino appeared on Weiss\\u2019s Honesty with Bari Weiss podcast in May, and the two were effusive in praising each other. \\u201cThe private Dana is even more gracious and shining than the public one,\\u201d Weiss said. \\u201cYou are a person who models, frankly, just classy behavior, the kind of class that I think a lot of people have forgotten.\\u201d Perino described herself as \\u201ca huge fan\\u201d of Weiss and her wife, Nellie Bowles, and said that their website the Free Press is \\u201cone of the best things that has kept me more informed and smarter, and also super entertained\\u201d. In chatter among employees, another name that has come up \\u2013 but isn\\u2019t likely in serious consideration \\u2013 is Shepard Smith, a former Fox News anchor, who resigned suddenly from the network in 2019. He signed with financial network CNBC to anchor a nightly newscast, but the experiment failed and he left the network in 2022. Since then, Smith has kept a low profile. Even if Weiss can land a big-name outsider, it\\u2019s an open question whether it would actually make a difference. CBS News has gone through a host of evening news anchors \\u2013 since 2011, the show has been hosted by Katie Couric, Scott Pelley, Anthony Mason, Jeff Glor and O\\u2019Donnell, in addition to the current pairing \\u2013 but none have been able to change the evening news pecking order. And with every switch behind the anchor desk, \\u201cyou have sent viewers away each time\\u201d, said a former CBS News executive who requested anonymity to speak candidly. Generally, viewers tend to stick with their evening news show of choice and seem unwilling to try out the competition. While NBC recently had a change in the anchor chair, with Tom Llamas replacing longtime anchor Lester Holt, ABC has seen continuity with David Muir leading the show since 2014. This season, Muir\\u2019s show has averaged 7.5 million viewers, comfortably ahead of NBC (5.7 million viewers) and far ahead of CBS (3.7 million viewers). \\u201cShe\\u2019s got a disaster on her hands at the Evening News and she\\u2019s got to fix the Evening News, and that\\u2019s got to be her new project,\\u201d said Tom Bettag, a lecturer at the University of Maryland\\u2019s journalism school who spent 22 years at CBS News, including a five-year stint as executive producer of the nightly show under Dan Rather. While the show\\u2019s ratings aren\\u2019t what they were, Bettag said the show is still essential to the identity of the network, not to mention a reliable source of advertiser revenue. \\u201cIf they have a really strong Evening News, it lifts the whole place,\\u201d he added. CBS News employees \\u2013 who were not authorized to comment \\u2013 were less specific about what needs to change on the evening show and who the network should pick to anchor. \\u201cWhat they need is someone who plays a very good anchor man and hopefully has journalistic chops and a very talented show-runner,\\u201d one staffer told the Guardian, while another was more concise: \\u201cWe need to just do a damn newscast. Don\\u2019t overthink it.\\u201d The CBS Evening News may not hold the place in society it once did, but what Weiss (and Cibrowski) decide to do with the show could hint at her longterm strategy and provide an early signal of whether she might be successful in turning around the network\\u2019s fortunes. \\u201cI wouldn\\u2019t say it\\u2019s the most important decision, but it\\u2019s probably the most telling decision, about where she\\u2019s taking the direction of the company,\\u201d the former CBS News executive said.\",\"charCount\":\"5857\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/jeremy-barr\\\">Jeremy Barr<\\/a> in Washington\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL),
(144, NULL, NULL, 'us-news/2025/oct/19/trump-briefing-news-at-a-glance-latest', 'Trump news at a glance: Inflatable costumes aplenty as millions march against president', 'Republicans mostly silent as protesters turn out in every state to peacefully reject authoritarianism in No Kings rallies. Key US politics stories from Saturday 18 October at a glance', 'Americans in every state marched in protest against the Trump administration, giving voice to concerns that the country is sliding into authoritarianism. Millions turned out nationwide with signs, marching bands, a huge banner with the US constitution’s preamble that people could sign, and inflatable costumes ranging from bananas to SpongeBob SquarePants to frogs, which have in particular emerged as a sign of resistance beginning in Portland, Oregon. The rallies are a turnaround from just six months ago, when Democrats seemed at a loss as to how to counter Republicans’ grip of the White House and both houses of Congress after stinging national election losses. “What we are seeing from the Democrats is some spine,” Ezra Levin, a co-founder of Indivisible, a key organizing group, told the Associated Press. “The worst thing the Democrats could do right now is surrender.” ‘We are here to stand firm,’ Chicago mayor tells No Kings protesters Chicago’s mayor, Brandon Johnson, told a crowd on Saturday that the Trump administration had “decided that they want a rematch of the civil war”, which the white supremacist Confederacy lost to the Union in the 19th century. “We are here to stand firm and stand committed that we will not bend, we will not bow, we will not cower, we will not submit,” Johnson said. “We do not want troops in our city.” Read the full story Republicans subdued as millions march Republican voices were mostly silent as No Kings rallies and marches against Trump administration policies unfurled on Saturday, many in the spirit of a street party that countered the “hate America” depiction advanced by senior members of the party. Read the full story Survivors of US strike on alleged drug boat may be sent to Colombia and Ecuador The Trump administration is moving to send the two survivors of Thursday’s strike in the Caribbean overseas to Colombia and Ecuador rather than seek long-term military detention for them, four US officials and a source familiar with the matter told Reuters on Saturday. It means that the US military will not have to grapple with thorny legal issues surrounding military detention for suspected drug traffickers, whose alleged crimes do not fall neatly under the laws of war, legal experts say. Read the full story US Senate poised to approve industry lobbyist to lead chemical safety at EPA The Senate is expected to approve Donald Trump’s nomination of an industry lobbyist to lead the US Environmental Protection Agency’s chemical safety office. If the nominee, Douglas Troutman, is confirmed, the top four toxics office positions at the EPA will be held by former chemical industry lobbyists, raising new fears about the health and safety of the American public, consumers and workers, campaigners say. Read the full story US border authorities tell airlines to disregard ‘X’ sex markers on passports US Customs and Border Protection implemented a rule this week that will require airlines to disregard “X” sex markers on passports and input an “M” or “F” marker instead. While the courts have continued to prevent the Trump administration from outright banning a third gender marker, this week’s rule can still serve to make the lives of trans and non-binary people more difficult, said Andy Izenson, senior legal director at the Chosen Family Law Center. Read the full story What else happened today: Disgraced former House member George Santos walked free from prison, provoking criticism from both sides of the political spectrum. Robert Zimmerman, the Democratic candidate Santos beat in 2022 to represent New York’s third congressional district, said in a statement that he had “no doubt that Santos will ultimately end up in Trump’s cabinet”. A Vermont state lawmaker has resigned over racist and antisemitic chat messages that circulated within the Young Republican political group, another substantial consequence in a scandal that on Friday saw the New York state Young Republicans’ charter revoked. Catching up? Here’s what happened on 17 October 2025.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/oct/19/trump-briefing-news-at-a-glance-latest', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/652516b92287eb4afaabdec8f247440f4a7dda5e/1314_355_5155_4125/500.jpg', '2025-10-19 09:31:14', '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/19\\/trump-briefing-news-at-a-glance-latest\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-19T02:31:14Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Trump news at a glance: Inflatable costumes aplenty as millions march against president\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/19\\/trump-briefing-news-at-a-glance-latest\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/19\\/trump-briefing-news-at-a-glance-latest\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Trump news at a glance: Inflatable costumes aplenty as millions march against president\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Republicans mostly silent as protesters turn out in every state to peacefully reject authoritarianism in No Kings rallies. Key US politics stories from Saturday 18 October at a glance<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"Republicans mostly silent as protesters turn out in every state to peacefully reject authoritarianism in No Kings rallies. Key US politics stories from Saturday 18 October at a glance\",\"byline\":\"Guardian staff\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"652516b92287eb4afaabdec8f247440f4a7dda5e\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/652516b92287eb4afaabdec8f247440f4a7dda5e\\/76_447_6384_4033\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"People in inflatable costumes attend the No Kings rally in Portland, Oregon on Saturday. \\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"632\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">People in inflatable costumes attend the No Kings rally in Portland, Oregon on Saturday. <\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Timothy J Gonzalez\\/ZUMA Press Wire\\/Shutterstock<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>Americans in every state <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/no-kings-protests-events-states\\\">marched in protest<\\/a> against the Trump administration, giving voice to concerns that the country is sliding into authoritarianism.<\\/p> <p>Millions turned out nationwide with signs, marching bands, a huge banner with the US constitution\\u2019s preamble that people could sign, and inflatable costumes ranging from bananas to SpongeBob SquarePants to frogs, which have in particular emerged as a sign of resistance beginning in Portland, Oregon.<\\/p> <p>The rallies are a turnaround from just six months ago, when Democrats seemed at a loss as to how to counter Republicans\\u2019 grip of the White House and both houses of Congress after stinging national election losses.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cWhat we are seeing from the Democrats is some spine,\\u201d Ezra Levin, a co-founder of Indivisible, a key organizing group, told the Associated Press. \\u201cThe worst thing the Democrats could do right now is surrender.\\u201d<\\/p>  <h2>\\u2018We are here to stand firm,\\u2019 Chicago mayor tells No Kings protesters<\\/h2>  <p>Chicago\\u2019s mayor, Brandon Johnson, told a crowd on Saturday that the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> had \\u201cdecided that they want a rematch of the civil war\\u201d, which the white supremacist Confederacy lost to the Union in the 19th century. <\\/p> <p>\\u201cWe are here to stand firm and stand committed that we will not bend, we will not bow, we will not cower, we will not submit,\\u201d Johnson said. \\u201cWe do not want troops in our city.\\u201d<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/no-kings-protests-events-states\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Republicans subdued as millions march<\\/h2>  <p>Republican voices were mostly silent as No Kings rallies and marches against Trump administration policies unfurled on Saturday, many in the spirit of a street party that countered the \\u201chate America\\u201d depiction advanced by senior members of the party.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/no-kings-protest-rally-republicans\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Survivors of US strike on alleged drug boat may be sent to Colombia and Ecuador<\\/h2>  <p>The <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> is moving to send the two survivors of Thursday\\u2019s strike in the Caribbean overseas to Colombia and Ecuador rather than seek long-term military detention for them, four US officials and a source familiar with the matter told Reuters on Saturday. <\\/p> <p>It means that the US military will not have to grapple with thorny legal issues surrounding military detention for suspected drug traffickers, whose alleged crimes do not fall neatly under the laws of war, legal experts say.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/us-military-strike-survivors\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>US Senate poised to approve industry lobbyist to lead chemical safety at EPA<\\/h2>  <p>The Senate is expected to approve Donald Trump\\u2019s nomination of an industry lobbyist to lead the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/environment\\/epa\\\">US Environmental Protection Agency\\u2019s<\\/a> chemical safety office.<\\/p> <p>If the nominee, Douglas Troutman, is confirmed, the top four toxics office positions at the EPA will be held by former chemical industry lobbyists, raising new fears about the health and safety of the American public, consumers and workers, campaigners say.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/senate-epa-confirmation-douglas-troutman-lobbyist\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>US border authorities tell airlines to disregard \\u2018X\\u2019 sex markers on passports<\\/h2>  <p>US Customs and Border Protection <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.cbp.gov\\/sites\\/default\\/files\\/2025-07\\/clp_bulletin_executive_order_on_m-f_gender_20250707.pdf\\\">implemented a rule this week<\\/a> that will require airlines to disregard \\u201cX\\u201d sex markers on passports and input an \\u201cM\\u201d or \\u201cF\\u201d marker instead.<\\/p> <p>While the courts have continued to prevent the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> from outright banning a third gender marker, this week\\u2019s rule can still serve to make the lives of trans and non-binary people more difficult, said Andy Izenson, senior legal director at the Chosen Family Law Center.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/airlines-passports-x-sex-marker\\\"><sub>Read the full story <\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>What else happened today:<\\/h2>  <ul> <li><p><strong>Disgraced former House member George Santos walked free from prison, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/george-santos-released-from-prison-new-jersey\\\">provoking criticism from both sides of the political spectrum<\\/a><\\/strong>. Robert Zimmerman, the Democratic candidate Santos beat in 2022 to represent New York\\u2019s third congressional district, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/x.com\\/ZimmermanRob\\/status\\/1979335247205667016\\\">said in a statement<\\/a> that he had \\u201cno doubt that Santos will ultimately end up in Trump\\u2019s cabinet\\u201d.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p><strong>A Vermont state lawmaker has <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/vermont-republican-resigns-racist-antisemitic-chat\\\">resigned over racist and antisemitic chat messages<\\/a> that circulated within the Young Republican political group<\\/strong>, another substantial consequence in a scandal that on Friday saw the New York state Young Republicans\\u2019 charter revoked.<\\/p><\\/li> <\\/ul>  <p>Catching up?<em> <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/18\\/trump-briefing-news-at-a-glance-latest\\\">Here\\u2019s what happened on 17 October 2025<\\/a>.<\\/em><\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"code\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;script src=&quot;https:\\/\\/uploads.guim.co.uk\\/2025\\/01\\/21\\/article-button.js&quot;&gt;&lt;script&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>\",\"wordcount\":\"651\",\"displayHint\":\"qAndA\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-19T02:31:14Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-10-19T02:32:39Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3f9ca\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/652516b92287eb4afaabdec8f247440f4a7dda5e\\/1314_355_5155_4125\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"Americans in every state marched in protest against the Trump administration, giving voice to concerns that the country is sliding into authoritarianism. Millions turned out nationwide with signs, marching bands, a huge banner with the US constitution\\u2019s preamble that people could sign, and inflatable costumes ranging from bananas to SpongeBob SquarePants to frogs, which have in particular emerged as a sign of resistance beginning in Portland, Oregon. The rallies are a turnaround from just six months ago, when Democrats seemed at a loss as to how to counter Republicans\\u2019 grip of the White House and both houses of Congress after stinging national election losses. \\u201cWhat we are seeing from the Democrats is some spine,\\u201d Ezra Levin, a co-founder of Indivisible, a key organizing group, told the Associated Press. \\u201cThe worst thing the Democrats could do right now is surrender.\\u201d \\u2018We are here to stand firm,\\u2019 Chicago mayor tells No Kings protesters Chicago\\u2019s mayor, Brandon Johnson, told a crowd on Saturday that the Trump administration had \\u201cdecided that they want a rematch of the civil war\\u201d, which the white supremacist Confederacy lost to the Union in the 19th century. \\u201cWe are here to stand firm and stand committed that we will not bend, we will not bow, we will not cower, we will not submit,\\u201d Johnson said. \\u201cWe do not want troops in our city.\\u201d Read the full story Republicans subdued as millions march Republican voices were mostly silent as No Kings rallies and marches against Trump administration policies unfurled on Saturday, many in the spirit of a street party that countered the \\u201chate America\\u201d depiction advanced by senior members of the party. Read the full story Survivors of US strike on alleged drug boat may be sent to Colombia and Ecuador The Trump administration is moving to send the two survivors of Thursday\\u2019s strike in the Caribbean overseas to Colombia and Ecuador rather than seek long-term military detention for them, four US officials and a source familiar with the matter told Reuters on Saturday. It means that the US military will not have to grapple with thorny legal issues surrounding military detention for suspected drug traffickers, whose alleged crimes do not fall neatly under the laws of war, legal experts say. Read the full story US Senate poised to approve industry lobbyist to lead chemical safety at EPA The Senate is expected to approve Donald Trump\\u2019s nomination of an industry lobbyist to lead the US Environmental Protection Agency\\u2019s chemical safety office. If the nominee, Douglas Troutman, is confirmed, the top four toxics office positions at the EPA will be held by former chemical industry lobbyists, raising new fears about the health and safety of the American public, consumers and workers, campaigners say. Read the full story US border authorities tell airlines to disregard \\u2018X\\u2019 sex markers on passports US Customs and Border Protection implemented a rule this week that will require airlines to disregard \\u201cX\\u201d sex markers on passports and input an \\u201cM\\u201d or \\u201cF\\u201d marker instead. While the courts have continued to prevent the Trump administration from outright banning a third gender marker, this week\\u2019s rule can still serve to make the lives of trans and non-binary people more difficult, said Andy Izenson, senior legal director at the Chosen Family Law Center. Read the full story What else happened today: Disgraced former House member George Santos walked free from prison, provoking criticism from both sides of the political spectrum. Robert Zimmerman, the Democratic candidate Santos beat in 2022 to represent New York\\u2019s third congressional district, said in a statement that he had \\u201cno doubt that Santos will ultimately end up in Trump\\u2019s cabinet\\u201d. A Vermont state lawmaker has resigned over racist and antisemitic chat messages that circulated within the Young Republican political group, another substantial consequence in a scandal that on Friday saw the New York state Young Republicans\\u2019 charter revoked. Catching up? Here\\u2019s what happened on 17 October 2025.\",\"charCount\":\"4029\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"Guardian staff\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL);
