(147, NULL, NULL, 'business/grogonomics/2025/jun/05/the-good-news-household-living-standards-are-on-the-rise-the-bad-news-just-about-everything-else', 'The good news? Household living standards are on the rise. The bad news? Just about everything else | Greg Jericho', 'Australia’s weak economic growth is not surprising when you factor in what’s going on with households, private investment, trade and government spending', 'There were early signs that the March GDP figures were not going to be good. To start with, the Bureau of Statistics’ new measure of household spending that covers about two-thirds of all household spending had already revealed that spending for the quarter was flat compared with a 1.6% jump in December quarter last year. So household spending was worse. Then last week the private capital expenditure figures revealed a 0.1% fall in investment in buildings and engineering, compared with a 0.2% rise in the December 2024 quarter. So private investment was worse. On Tuesday, the balance of payments revealed that trade in the first three months of this year was expected to “detract 0.1%pts from the March quarter” compared with adding 0.2%pts in December. So trade was worse. Just to top it off, on Tuesday the figures for government spending and investment showed that public demand fell in the March quarter and would also detract 0.1%pts from GDP growth compared with it adding 0.2%pts to GDP growth last December. So the impact of the public sector was worse. To be honest, once you take away households, private investment, trade and government spending, you really are not left with much. So it came to be. In the March quarter of this year, GDP growth was just 0.2%, down from 0.6% in the December quarter. The only good news is the March quarter last year was pretty dire as well, so all up it meant annual growth remained steady at a still extremely weak 1.3%. If the graph does not display click here This weak growth meant that per capita GDP fell again – the ninth quarter out of the past 11. This is not a good state of affairs, and certainly does not accord with the views of the Reserve Bank back in April when it looked at the first three months of this year and suggested that “the limited information available about activity in early 2025 suggested that the pick-up in GDP growth had been sustained”. Ahh well, at least they can say they were not wrong for long? Well no. In the minutes of the May board meeting released this week the RBA now suggested that “GDP growth had increased in the December quarter 2024 and year-ended growth looked to have picked up a little further in the March quarter”. Going from 1.3% growth in December to 1.3% growth in March is hardly “picked up”. The May Statement on Monetary Policy also predicted annual GDP growth in June of 1.8%. To get to that level, the economy would need to grow in April, May and June by 0.7% – the strongest quarter growth for three years. Here’s hoping … So what drove the growth that was there? Households were the biggest contributor to growth – although as in all things the context is key. Their contribution to the growth of the economy in the March quarter was about half what you would normally expect. If the graph does not display click here And a big reason for the increase in consumption was a jump in spending on electricity, gas and other fuels – due to the ending of some of the state government energy rebates (which also had an impact on inflation). That is not the type of spending you want to see driving households. All up the level of household consumption is well down on what would have been expected before the pandemic. The Reserve Bank’s interest rate rises did their job – they snuffed out spending. Clearly more rate cuts are needed to undo that damage and it is quite extraordinary that the RBA is so sanguine about it all: If the graph does not display click here The overall level of household spending and private-sector investment quickly rules out the use of the phrase “strong” when searching for a term to describe what is going on: If the graph does not display click here And that’s not surprising because while home loan rates have come down, the average discounted rate is still more than 300 basis point higher than it was at the start of 2022. But for small business owners taking out an overdraft loan, things are even worse – the rate is 400 basis point higher: If the graph does not display click here But let us not be too negative. One very good piece of news is that household living standards are on the rise. After two years, finally household disposable income per capita is above the level it was in March 2020: If the graph does not display click here One reason for this was there was a very slight decline in the level of mortgage repayments, due to the rate cut in February. This cut actually helped increased living standards in the first three months of this year. But that was a very small repair, given since March 2022 mortgage repayments have contributed about 63% of the fall in living standards: If the graph does not display click here That’s a sizeable chunk and it reinforces the damage that is done when the RBA so badly misreads the economy as it has. These figures highlight that not only should the Reserve Bank have cut rates in April but having made that error it compounded it by not cutting rates by at least 50 basis points last month. So far this year the RBA has kept misreading the economic situation and erred on the side of caution. Let us hope these weak figures spur it to cut rates when it meets next month and not suggest it still needs more time to see what is going on. Greg Jericho is a Guardian columnist and policy director at the Centre for Future Work', 'https://www.theguardian.com/business/grogonomics/2025/jun/05/the-good-news-household-living-standards-are-on-the-rise-the-bad-news-just-about-everything-else', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/514ceb1ea9696464749d424d9d11a7c6cf9f75be/307_0_3073_2460/500.jpg', '2025-06-04 22:00:46', '{\"id\":\"business\\/grogonomics\\/2025\\/jun\\/05\\/the-good-news-household-living-standards-are-on-the-rise-the-bad-news-just-about-everything-else\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"business\",\"sectionName\":\"Business\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-06-04T15:00:46Z\",\"webTitle\":\"The good news? Household living standards are on the rise. The bad news? Just about everything else | Greg Jericho\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/grogonomics\\/2025\\/jun\\/05\\/the-good-news-household-living-standards-are-on-the-rise-the-bad-news-just-about-everything-else\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/business\\/grogonomics\\/2025\\/jun\\/05\\/the-good-news-household-living-standards-are-on-the-rise-the-bad-news-just-about-everything-else\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"The good news? Household living standards are on the rise. The bad news? Just about everything else\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Australia\\u2019s weak economic growth is not surprising when you factor in what\\u2019s going on with households, private investment, trade and government spending<\\/p><ul><li><p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/australia-news\\/live\\/2025\\/jun\\/05\\/australia-news-live-matt-kean-climate-target-jeremy-rockliff-tasmania-no-confidence-nicolette-boele-bradfield-ntwnfb\\\">Australia news live: latest politics updates<\\/a><\\/p><\\/li><li><p>Get our <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/email-newsletters?CMP=cvau_sfl\\\">breaking news email<\\/a>, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/app.adjust.com\\/w4u7jx3\\\">free app<\\/a> or <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/australia-news\\/series\\/full-story?CMP=cvau_sfl\\\">daily news podcast<\\/a><\\/p><\\/li><\\/ul>\",\"trailText\":\"Australia\\u2019s weak economic growth is not surprising when you factor in what\\u2019s going on with households, private investment, trade and government spending\",\"byline\":\"Greg Jericho\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"514ceb1ea9696464749d424d9d11a7c6cf9f75be\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/514ceb1ea9696464749d424d9d11a7c6cf9f75be\\/0_0_3688_2460\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"FILE PHOTO: Office workers walk the streets of Sydney, Australia December 7, 2016 as the latest Australian GDP figure released Wednesday indicated a 0.5% contraction in the third quarter.REUTERS\\/Jason Reed\\/File Photo\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"667\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">\\u2018In the March quarter of this year, GDP growth was just 0.2%, down from 0.6% in the December quarter,\\u2019 Greg Jericho writes.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Jason Reed\\/Reuters<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>There were early signs that the March GDP figures were not going to be good.<\\/p> <p>To start with, the Bureau of Statistics\\u2019 new <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.abs.gov.au\\/statistics\\/economy\\/finance\\/monthly-household-spending-indicator\\/latest-release\\\">measure of household spending<\\/a> that covers about two-thirds of all household spending had already revealed that spending for the quarter was flat compared with a 1.6% jump in December quarter last year. So household spending was worse.<\\/p> <p>Then last week the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.abs.gov.au\\/statistics\\/economy\\/business-indicators\\/private-new-capital-expenditure-and-expected-expenditure-australia\\/mar-2025\\\">private capital expenditure figures<\\/a> revealed a 0.1% fall in investment in buildings and engineering, compared with a 0.2% rise in the December 2024 quarter. So private investment was worse.<\\/p> <p>On Tuesday, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.abs.gov.au\\/statistics\\/economy\\/international-trade\\/balance-payments-and-international-investment-position-australia\\/mar-2025\\\">the balance of payments<\\/a> revealed that trade in the first three months of this year was expected to \\u201cdetract 0.1%pts from the March quarter\\u201d compared with adding 0.2%pts in December. So trade was worse.<\\/p> <p>Just to top it off, on Tuesday the figures <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.abs.gov.au\\/statistics\\/economy\\/government\\/government-finance-statistics-australia\\/mar-2025\\\">for government spending and investment<\\/a> showed that public demand fell in the March quarter and would also detract 0.1%pts from GDP growth compared with it adding 0.2%pts to GDP growth last December. So the impact of the public sector was worse.<\\/p> <p>To be honest, once you take away households, private investment, trade and government spending, you really are not left with much.<\\/p> <p>So it came to be.<\\/p> <p>In the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.abs.gov.au\\/statistics\\/economy\\/national-accounts\\/australian-national-accounts-national-income-expenditure-and-product\\/mar-2025#key-statistics\\\">March quarter of this year, GDP growth<\\/a> was just 0.2%, down from 0.6% in the December quarter. The only good news is the March quarter last year was pretty dire as well, so all up it meant annual growth remained steady at a still extremely weak 1.3%.<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"Australia\\u2019s GDP growth\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:393px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-wtTvd&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/wtTvd\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-wtTvd&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/wtTvd\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/wtTvd\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>This weak growth meant that per capita GDP fell again \\u2013 the ninth quarter out of the past 11.<\\/p> <p>This is not a good state of affairs, and certainly does not accord with the views of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.rba.gov.au\\/monetary-policy\\/rba-board-minutes\\/2025\\/2025-04-01.html\\\">the Reserve Bank back in April<\\/a> when it looked at the first three months of this year and suggested that \\u201cthe limited information available about activity in early 2025 suggested that the pick-up in GDP growth had been sustained\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>Ahh well, at least they can say they were not wrong for long?<\\/p> <p>Well no. In the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.rba.gov.au\\/monetary-policy\\/rba-board-minutes\\/2025\\/2025-05-20.html\\\">minutes of the May board meeting<\\/a> released this week the RBA now suggested that \\u201cGDP growth had increased in the December quarter 2024 and year-ended growth looked to have picked up a little further in the March quarter\\u201d. Going from 1.3% growth in December to 1.3% growth in March is hardly \\u201cpicked up\\u201d.<\\/p> <p>The May <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.rba.gov.au\\/publications\\/smp\\/2025\\/may\\/outlook.html#4-6-detailed-forecast-information\\\">Statement on Monetary Policy<\\/a> also predicted annual GDP growth in June of 1.8%. To get to that level, the economy would need to grow in April, May and June by 0.7% \\u2013 the strongest quarter growth for three years. Here\\u2019s hoping \\u2026<\\/p> <p>So what drove the growth that was there?<\\/p> <p>Households were the biggest contributor to growth \\u2013 although as in all things the context is key. Their contribution to the growth of the economy in the March quarter was about half what you would normally expect.<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"Contributions to GDP growth\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:400px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-zMCTj&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/zMCTj\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-zMCTj&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/zMCTj\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/zMCTj\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>And a big reason for the increase in consumption was a jump in spending on electricity, gas and other fuels \\u2013 due to the ending of some of the state government energy rebates (<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/business\\/grogonomics\\/2025\\/may\\/01\\/by-getting-tangled-up-on-inflation-and-exaggerating-numbers-peter-dutton-has-blown-the-opportunity-he-was-handed\\\">which also had an impact on inflation<\\/a>). That is not the type of spending you want to see driving households.<\\/p> <p>All up the level of household consumption is well down on what would have been expected before the pandemic. The Reserve Bank\\u2019s interest rate rises did their job \\u2013 they snuffed out spending. Clearly more rate cuts are needed to undo that damage and it is quite extraordinary that the RBA is so sanguine about it all:<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"Household spending remains well down on pre-pandemic trend levels\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:400px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-FTOto&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/FTOto\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-FTOto&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/FTOto\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/FTOto\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>The overall level of household spending and private-sector investment quickly rules out the use of the phrase \\u201cstrong\\u201d when searching for a term to describe what is going on:<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"The private sector remains weak\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:400px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-xoLfP&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/xoLfP\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-xoLfP&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/xoLfP\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/xoLfP\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>And that\\u2019s not surprising because while home loan rates have come down, the average discounted rate is still more than 300 basis point higher than it was at the start of 2022. But for small business owners taking out an overdraft loan, things are even worse \\u2013 the rate is 400 basis point higher:<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"Small business loan rates have not fallen as much as home loan rates\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:400px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-VvcNF&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/VvcNF\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-VvcNF&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/VvcNF\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/VvcNF\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>But let us not be too negative. One very good piece of news is that household living standards are on the rise. After two years, finally household disposable income per capita is above the level it was in March 2020:<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"Household living standards are now above pre-pandemic levels\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:532px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-GAI2x&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/GAI2x\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-GAI2x&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/GAI2x\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/GAI2x\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>One reason for this was there was a very slight decline in the level of mortgage repayments, due to the rate cut in February. This cut actually helped increased living standards in the first three months of this year. But that was a very small repair, given since March 2022 mortgage repayments have contributed about 63% of the fall in living standards:<\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"Change in living standards: March 2022 to March 2025\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;min-height:400px&quot; id=&quot;datawrapper-vis-Ip6zc&quot;&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;text\\/javascript&quot; defer src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/Ip6zc\\/embed.js&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; data-target=&quot;#datawrapper-vis-Ip6zc&quot;&gt;&lt;\\/script&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:\\/\\/datawrapper.dwcdn.net\\/Ip6zc\\/full.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; \\/&gt;&lt;\\/noscript&gt;&lt;\\/div&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.datawrapper.de\\/_\\/Ip6zc\\/\\\">If the graph does not display click here<\\/a><\\/p> <p>That\\u2019s a sizeable chunk and it reinforces the damage that is done when the RBA so badly misreads the economy as it has. These figures highlight that not only should the Reserve Bank have cut rates in April but having made that error it compounded it by not cutting rates by at least 50 basis points last month.<\\/p> <p>So far this year the RBA has kept misreading the economic situation and erred on the side of caution. Let us hope these weak figures spur it to cut rates when it meets next month and not suggest it still needs more time to see what is going on.<\\/p> <ul> <li><p>Greg Jericho is a Guardian columnist and policy director at the Centre for Future Work<\\/p><\\/li> <\\/ul>\",\"wordcount\":\"955\",\"commentCloseDate\":\"2025-06-05T07:00:00Z\",\"commentable\":\"true\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-06-04T15:00:46Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-06-04T23:27:36Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"AUS\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x2dhp3\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/514ceb1ea9696464749d424d9d11a7c6cf9f75be\\/307_0_3073_2460\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"There were early signs that the March GDP figures were not going to be good. To start with, the Bureau of Statistics\\u2019 new measure of household spending that covers about two-thirds of all household spending had already revealed that spending for the quarter was flat compared with a 1.6% jump in December quarter last year. So household spending was worse. Then last week the private capital expenditure figures revealed a 0.1% fall in investment in buildings and engineering, compared with a 0.2% rise in the December 2024 quarter. So private investment was worse. On Tuesday, the balance of payments revealed that trade in the first three months of this year was expected to \\u201cdetract 0.1%pts from the March quarter\\u201d compared with adding 0.2%pts in December. So trade was worse. Just to top it off, on Tuesday the figures for government spending and investment showed that public demand fell in the March quarter and would also detract 0.1%pts from GDP growth compared with it adding 0.2%pts to GDP growth last December. So the impact of the public sector was worse. To be honest, once you take away households, private investment, trade and government spending, you really are not left with much. So it came to be. In the March quarter of this year, GDP growth was just 0.2%, down from 0.6% in the December quarter. The only good news is the March quarter last year was pretty dire as well, so all up it meant annual growth remained steady at a still extremely weak 1.3%. If the graph does not display click here This weak growth meant that per capita GDP fell again \\u2013 the ninth quarter out of the past 11. This is not a good state of affairs, and certainly does not accord with the views of the Reserve Bank back in April when it looked at the first three months of this year and suggested that \\u201cthe limited information available about activity in early 2025 suggested that the pick-up in GDP growth had been sustained\\u201d. Ahh well, at least they can say they were not wrong for long? Well no. In the minutes of the May board meeting released this week the RBA now suggested that \\u201cGDP growth had increased in the December quarter 2024 and year-ended growth looked to have picked up a little further in the March quarter\\u201d. Going from 1.3% growth in December to 1.3% growth in March is hardly \\u201cpicked up\\u201d. The May Statement on Monetary Policy also predicted annual GDP growth in June of 1.8%. To get to that level, the economy would need to grow in April, May and June by 0.7% \\u2013 the strongest quarter growth for three years. Here\\u2019s hoping \\u2026 So what drove the growth that was there? Households were the biggest contributor to growth \\u2013 although as in all things the context is key. Their contribution to the growth of the economy in the March quarter was about half what you would normally expect. If the graph does not display click here And a big reason for the increase in consumption was a jump in spending on electricity, gas and other fuels \\u2013 due to the ending of some of the state government energy rebates (which also had an impact on inflation). That is not the type of spending you want to see driving households. All up the level of household consumption is well down on what would have been expected before the pandemic. The Reserve Bank\\u2019s interest rate rises did their job \\u2013 they snuffed out spending. Clearly more rate cuts are needed to undo that damage and it is quite extraordinary that the RBA is so sanguine about it all: If the graph does not display click here The overall level of household spending and private-sector investment quickly rules out the use of the phrase \\u201cstrong\\u201d when searching for a term to describe what is going on: If the graph does not display click here And that\\u2019s not surprising because while home loan rates have come down, the average discounted rate is still more than 300 basis point higher than it was at the start of 2022. But for small business owners taking out an overdraft loan, things are even worse \\u2013 the rate is 400 basis point higher: If the graph does not display click here But let us not be too negative. One very good piece of news is that household living standards are on the rise. After two years, finally household disposable income per capita is above the level it was in March 2020: If the graph does not display click here One reason for this was there was a very slight decline in the level of mortgage repayments, due to the rate cut in February. This cut actually helped increased living standards in the first three months of this year. But that was a very small repair, given since March 2022 mortgage repayments have contributed about 63% of the fall in living standards: If the graph does not display click here That\\u2019s a sizeable chunk and it reinforces the damage that is done when the RBA so badly misreads the economy as it has. These figures highlight that not only should the Reserve Bank have cut rates in April but having made that error it compounded it by not cutting rates by at least 50 basis points last month. So far this year the RBA has kept misreading the economic situation and erred on the side of caution. Let us hope these weak figures spur it to cut rates when it meets next month and not suggest it still needs more time to see what is going on. Greg Jericho is a Guardian columnist and policy director at the Centre for Future Work\",\"charCount\":\"5328\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/greg-jericho\\\">Greg Jericho<\\/a>\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL),
(148, NULL, NULL, 'us-news/2025/sep/20/police-arrest-man-suspected-of-shooting-into-a-sacramento-abc-news-station', 'Police arrest man suspected of shooting into a Sacramento ABC news station', 'Police say the ABC10 building was occupied when shots were fired into the lobby but ‘no one was injured’', 'Police have arrested a man suspected of shooting into the lobby of Sacramento’s ABC affiliate on Friday. Though the shooting occurred just a day after protesters gathered outside to the station to condemn ABC’s suspension of Jimmy Kimmel’s late-night talkshow, Sacramento police said the motive in the case remained under investigation, with it not being immediately clear whether the gunfire was targeted or random. Anibal Hernandez Santana, 64, faces counts of assault with a deadly weapon, shooting into an occupied building, and negligent discharge of a firearm after his arrest in the case, Sacramento police said in a statement early Saturday. After he posted bail, the FBI arrested him with interference to communications of stations that are licensed by the federal government, according to officials. Shots were fired at ABC10, whose call letters are KXTV, just after 1.30pm Friday, police said. Officers spotted at least three gunshots into the window but said it was unclear whether they had been directed at the station building. The building was occupied at the time, but “fortunately, no one was injured”, said the Sacramento police’s public information officer, Anthony Gamble, during a news conference. Authorities confirmed that the gunshots appeared to have been fired from a vehicle. They asked witnesses with any information regarding the investigation to contact the Sacramento police’s dispatch center. Police said they arrested Hernandez with the help of the FBI after linking him to a car suspected of having been used to shoot at the station. He was arrested in Sacramento’s River Park neighborhood, which is in the north-eastern part of the city. On Thursday, video footage taken by the Sacramento Bee showed protesters gathered outside the ABC building, demonstrating against the suspension of Kimmel’s show after his commentary about the Trump administration’s response to the 10 September shooting death of far-right commentator Charlie Kirk at Utah Valley University. The protesters held up signs like “fight back”, “you’re next” and “first amendment”, referring to the part of the US constitution that guarantees US citizens the right to free speech. “What happened with Jimmy Kimmel yesterday really caused a lot of concern for our free speech rights,” one of the protesters told the Bee. Variety reported about the existence of an X account for Hernandez that contained “a steady stream of anti-Trump commentary”. On Thursday, the account reportedly posted: “Where is a good heart attack when we need it most?? Please Join in my thoughts and prayers for the physical demise of our fearful leader.” ABC10’s corporate owner, Tegna, issued a statement saying all of its employees were “safe and unharmed” after Friday’s gunfire. “While details are still limited … we are fully cooperating with law enforcement and have taken additional measures to ensure the continued safety of our employees,” the company’s statement said. The shots fired at the Sacramento news station came a week after authorities found a bomb had been placed under a news media vehicle in Salt Lake City, Utah. The bomb didn’t detonate, but two men were arrested and could face charges of illegal weapon possession as well as threats to terrorism.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/sep/20/police-arrest-man-suspected-of-shooting-into-a-sacramento-abc-news-station', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/62eab06ffc5ec32525b40d8d17cb57988be878e0/516_0_4028_3224/500.jpg', '2025-09-20 22:05:46', '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/20\\/police-arrest-man-suspected-of-shooting-into-a-sacramento-abc-news-station\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-09-20T15:05:46Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Police arrest man suspected of shooting into a Sacramento ABC news station\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/20\\/police-arrest-man-suspected-of-shooting-into-a-sacramento-abc-news-station\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/20\\/police-arrest-man-suspected-of-shooting-into-a-sacramento-abc-news-station\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Police arrest man suspected of shooting into a Sacramento ABC news station\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Police say the ABC10 building was occupied when shots were fired into the lobby but \\u2018no one was injured\\u2019<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"Police say the ABC10 building was occupied when shots were fired into the lobby but \\u2018no one was injured\\u2019\",\"byline\":\"Olivia Empson\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"62eab06ffc5ec32525b40d8d17cb57988be878e0\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/62eab06ffc5ec32525b40d8d17cb57988be878e0\\/516_0_4028_3224\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"a brick wall with a blue ABC10 sign on it and a window covered with a wooden board\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">A window that was stuck by gunfire is covered with a board at ABC10 (KXTV) in Sacramento, California, on 19 September 2025.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Fred Greaves\\/Reuters<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>Police have <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/x.com\\/SacPolice\\/status\\/1969316857544130856\\\">arrested<\\/a> a man suspected of shooting into the lobby of Sacramento\\u2019s <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/media\\/abc\\\">ABC<\\/a> affiliate on Friday.<\\/p> <p>Though the shooting occurred just a day after protesters gathered outside to the station to condemn ABC\\u2019s suspension of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/tv-and-radio\\/jimmy-kimmel\\\">Jimmy Kimmel<\\/a>\\u2019s late-night talkshow, Sacramento police said the motive in the case remained under investigation, with it not being immediately clear whether the gunfire was targeted or random.<\\/p> <p>Anibal Hernandez Santana, 64, faces counts of assault with a deadly weapon, shooting into an occupied building, and negligent discharge of a firearm after his arrest in the case, Sacramento police said in a statement early Saturday. After he posted bail, the FBI arrested him with interference to communications of stations that are licensed by the federal government, according to officials.<\\/p> <p>Shots were fired at ABC10, whose call letters are KXTV, just after 1.30pm Friday, police said. Officers spotted at least three gunshots into the window but said it was unclear whether they had been directed at the station building.<\\/p> <p>The building was occupied at the time, but \\u201cfortunately, no one was injured\\u201d, said the Sacramento police\\u2019s public information officer, Anthony Gamble, during a news <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=Dy3LmM1eLfM\\\">conference<\\/a>.<\\/p> <p>Authorities confirmed that the gunshots appeared to have been fired from a vehicle. They asked witnesses with any information regarding the investigation to contact the Sacramento police\\u2019s dispatch center.<\\/p> <p>Police said they arrested Hernandez with the help of the FBI after linking him to a car suspected of having been used to shoot at the station. He was arrested in Sacramento\\u2019s River Park neighborhood, which is in the north-eastern part of the city.<\\/p> <p>On Thursday, video<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?app=desktop&amp;v=1WML4A3-s0c\\\"> footage<\\/a> taken by the Sacramento Bee showed protesters gathered outside the ABC building, demonstrating against the suspension of Kimmel\\u2019s show after his commentary about the Trump administration\\u2019s response to the 10 September <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/charlie-kirk-shooting\\\">shooting death<\\/a> of far-right commentator Charlie Kirk at Utah Valley University.<\\/p> <p>The protesters held up signs like \\u201cfight back\\u201d, \\u201cyou\\u2019re next\\u201d and \\u201cfirst amendment\\u201d, referring to the part of the US constitution that guarantees US citizens the right to free speech.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cWhat happened with Jimmy Kimmel yesterday really caused a lot of concern for our free speech rights,\\u201d one of the protesters told the Bee.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/variety.com\\/2025\\/tv\\/news\\/abc-affiliate-sacramento-gunfire-kimmel-protest-1236524751\\/\\\">Variety<\\/a> reported about the existence of an X account for Hernandez that contained \\u201ca steady stream of anti-Trump commentary\\u201d. On Thursday, the account reportedly posted: \\u201cWhere is a good heart attack when we need it most?? Please Join in my thoughts and prayers for the physical demise of our fearful leader.\\u201d<\\/p> <p>ABC10\\u2019s corporate owner, Tegna, issued a statement saying all of its employees were \\u201csafe and unharmed\\u201d after Friday\\u2019s gunfire.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cWhile details are still limited \\u2026 we are fully cooperating with law enforcement and have taken additional measures to ensure the continued safety of our employees,\\u201d the company\\u2019s statement said.<\\/p> <p>The shots fired at the Sacramento news station came a week after authorities <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/sep\\/14\\/utah-arrest-explosive-device\\\">found a bomb<\\/a> had been placed under a news media vehicle in Salt Lake City, Utah. The bomb didn\\u2019t detonate, but two men were arrested and could face charges of illegal weapon possession as well as threats to terrorism.<\\/p>\",\"wordcount\":\"521\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-09-20T15:05:46Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-09-21T13:10:22Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x399ec\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/62eab06ffc5ec32525b40d8d17cb57988be878e0\\/516_0_4028_3224\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"Police have arrested a man suspected of shooting into the lobby of Sacramento\\u2019s ABC affiliate on Friday. Though the shooting occurred just a day after protesters gathered outside to the station to condemn ABC\\u2019s suspension of Jimmy Kimmel\\u2019s late-night talkshow, Sacramento police said the motive in the case remained under investigation, with it not being immediately clear whether the gunfire was targeted or random. Anibal Hernandez Santana, 64, faces counts of assault with a deadly weapon, shooting into an occupied building, and negligent discharge of a firearm after his arrest in the case, Sacramento police said in a statement early Saturday. After he posted bail, the FBI arrested him with interference to communications of stations that are licensed by the federal government, according to officials. Shots were fired at ABC10, whose call letters are KXTV, just after 1.30pm Friday, police said. Officers spotted at least three gunshots into the window but said it was unclear whether they had been directed at the station building. The building was occupied at the time, but \\u201cfortunately, no one was injured\\u201d, said the Sacramento police\\u2019s public information officer, Anthony Gamble, during a news conference. Authorities confirmed that the gunshots appeared to have been fired from a vehicle. They asked witnesses with any information regarding the investigation to contact the Sacramento police\\u2019s dispatch center. Police said they arrested Hernandez with the help of the FBI after linking him to a car suspected of having been used to shoot at the station. He was arrested in Sacramento\\u2019s River Park neighborhood, which is in the north-eastern part of the city. On Thursday, video footage taken by the Sacramento Bee showed protesters gathered outside the ABC building, demonstrating against the suspension of Kimmel\\u2019s show after his commentary about the Trump administration\\u2019s response to the 10 September shooting death of far-right commentator Charlie Kirk at Utah Valley University. The protesters held up signs like \\u201cfight back\\u201d, \\u201cyou\\u2019re next\\u201d and \\u201cfirst amendment\\u201d, referring to the part of the US constitution that guarantees US citizens the right to free speech. \\u201cWhat happened with Jimmy Kimmel yesterday really caused a lot of concern for our free speech rights,\\u201d one of the protesters told the Bee. Variety reported about the existence of an X account for Hernandez that contained \\u201ca steady stream of anti-Trump commentary\\u201d. On Thursday, the account reportedly posted: \\u201cWhere is a good heart attack when we need it most?? Please Join in my thoughts and prayers for the physical demise of our fearful leader.\\u201d ABC10\\u2019s corporate owner, Tegna, issued a statement saying all of its employees were \\u201csafe and unharmed\\u201d after Friday\\u2019s gunfire. \\u201cWhile details are still limited \\u2026 we are fully cooperating with law enforcement and have taken additional measures to ensure the continued safety of our employees,\\u201d the company\\u2019s statement said. The shots fired at the Sacramento news station came a week after authorities found a bomb had been placed under a news media vehicle in Salt Lake City, Utah. The bomb didn\\u2019t detonate, but two men were arrested and could face charges of illegal weapon possession as well as threats to terrorism.\",\"charCount\":\"3249\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"<a href=\\\"profile\\/olivia-rose-empson\\\">Olivia Empson<\\/a>\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL);
