(149, NULL, NULL, 'us-news/2025/oct/31/trump-administration-news-updates-today', 'Trump news at a glance: Friday rulings hamper administration on food stamps, voting access', 'President Trump received a trio of legal setbacks Friday– key US politics stories from 31 October at a glance', 'President Trump received a trio of legal setbacks Friday related to the government shutdown and his attempts to tweak voting access in US elections. First, two federal judges issued back-to-back rulings in separate cases ordering the administration to use contingency funds to continue paying for food stamps under the Snap program. One judge in Rhode Island blocked the Trump administration from suspending all food aid for millions of Americans, in a case brought by a group of US cities, non-profit organizations and a trade union. At almost the same time, in a separate but similar case, a judge in Massachusetts ruled that the government must continue to fund the program that helps low-income households stave off food insecurity, in a case brought by the Democratic attorneys general from 22 states and the District of Columbia and three governors who sued the administration. And later Friday, a US district judge in Washington DC ruled that Trump’s proof-of-citizenship directive to overhaul US elections was unconstitutional. “Because our constitution assigns responsibility for election regulation to the states and to Congress, this court holds that the president lacks the authority to direct such changes,” judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly wrote in her opinion. That’s a blow to the administration and its allies who have argued that such a mandate is necessary to restore public confidence that only Americans are voting in US elections. Trump administration blocked from suspending Snap benefits for millions of Americans Two federal judges issued back-to-back rulings on Friday in separate cases ordering the Trump administration to use contingency funds to continue paying for food stamps during the government shutdown. A federal judge in Rhode Island blocked the Trump administration from suspending all food aid for millions of Americans, in a case brought by a group of US cities, non-profit organizations and a trade union. Read the full story Trump can’t require citizenship proof on the federal voting form, judge rules Donald Trump’s request to add a documentary proof of citizenship requirement to the federal voter registration form cannot be enforced, a federal judge ruled today. US district judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly in Washington DC sided with Democratic and civil rights groups that sued the Trump administration over his executive order to overhaul US elections. She ruled that the proof-of-citizenship directive is an unconstitutional violation of the separation of powers, dealing a blow to the administration and its allies. Read the full story Justice department seeks 2020 election records from Georgia county Trump’s justice department on Thursday asked election officials in Fulton county, Georgia, to turn over records related to the 2020 election, a request that underscores how the administration is trying to revive one of the president’s biggest falsehoods about the election he lost five years ago. Investigators have cleared Fulton county of malfeasance in 2020. Nonetheless, a Republican majority on the board voted to reopen the investigation last year. Read the full story Harrison Ford lays into Trump on climate Harrison Ford has said that Donald Trump’s assault on measures to address the climate crisis “scares the shit out of me” and makes the US president among the worst criminals in history. In a blistering attack, Ford told the Guardian Trump “doesn’t have any policies, he has whims. It scares the shit out of me. The ignorance, the hubris, the lies, the perfidy. [Trump] knows better, but he’s an instrument of the status quo and he’s making money, hand over fist, while the world goes to hell in a handbasket.” Read the full story How Stephen Miller is creating an ‘anti-immigration machine’ The historic shifts in US immigration under Donald Trump have been dictated by Stephen Miller, the president’s immigration czar, who in recent months has turned the state department’s visa and refugee operations into what some current and former diplomats have described as a personal fiefdom. Read the full story What else happened today: Kristi Noem, the homeland security secretary, has said she will not suspend the US government’s aggressive immigration crackdown in Illinois over Halloween, denying a request from the state’s governor that children might enjoy the holiday “without fear”. Trump called on the Senate to scrap the filibuster, so that the Republican majority can bypass Democrats and reopen the federal government. The Senate majority leader, John Thune, a Republican known for defending Senate traditions, has repeatedly rejected proposals to weaken or remove the 60-vote rule. What is the filibuster and why does Trump want to get rid of it? Here’s what you need to know. More than half of Americans disapprove of Donald Trump’s demolition of the White House’s East Wing and the construction of a new ballroom, according to a new poll from the Washington Post, ABC News and Ipsos. According to the poll, 56% of the respondents disagree with Trump’s recent move while 28% are in favor of it. White House deputy chief of staff Stephen Miller was the driving force behind a purge of Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agents who had investigated Donald Trump, a new book reveals. Catching up? Here’s what happened 30 October 2025.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/oct/31/trump-administration-news-updates-today', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/3d29c5de3952fdcd7665b87c11f5c5a61443192b/609_0_5000_4000/500.jpg', '2025-11-01 08:01:09', '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/trump-administration-news-updates-today\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-11-01T01:01:09Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Trump news at a glance: Friday rulings hamper administration on food stamps, voting access\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/trump-administration-news-updates-today\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/trump-administration-news-updates-today\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Trump news at a glance: Friday rulings hamper administration on food stamps, voting access\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>President Trump received a trio of legal setbacks \\u2013 key US politics stories from 31 October at a glance<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"President Trump received a trio of legal setbacks Friday\\u2013 key US politics stories from 31 October at a glance\",\"byline\":\"Guardian staff\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"3d29c5de3952fdcd7665b87c11f5c5a61443192b\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/3d29c5de3952fdcd7665b87c11f5c5a61443192b\\/609_0_5000_4000\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"A \'We Accept (Food Stamps)\' sign hangs in the window of a grocery store on 31 October 31 in Miami, Florida.\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">A \'We Accept (Food Stamps)\' sign hangs in the window of a grocery store in Miami on Friday.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Joe Raedle\\/Getty Images<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>President Trump received a trio of legal setbacks Friday related to the government shutdown and his attempts to tweak voting access in US elections.<\\/p> <p>First, two federal judges issued back-to-back rulings in separate cases ordering the administration to use contingency funds to continue paying for food stamps under the Snap program.<\\/p> <p>One judge in <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/rhode-island\\\">Rhode Island<\\/a> blocked the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> from suspending all food aid for millions of Americans, in a case brought by a group of US cities, non-profit organizations and a trade union. At almost the same time, in a separate but similar case, a judge in <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/massachusetts\\\">Massachusetts<\\/a> ruled that the government must continue to fund the program that helps low-income households stave off food insecurity, in a case brought by the Democratic attorneys general from 22 states and the District of Columbia and three governors who sued the administration.<\\/p> <p>And later Friday, a US district judge in Washington DC ruled that Trump\\u2019s proof-of-citizenship directive to overhaul US elections was unconstitutional.<\\/p> <p>\\u201cBecause our constitution assigns responsibility for election regulation to the states and to Congress, this court holds that the president lacks the authority to direct such changes,\\u201d judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly wrote in her opinion.<\\/p> <p>That\\u2019s a blow to the administration and its allies who have argued that such a mandate is necessary to restore public confidence that only Americans are voting in US elections.<\\/p>  <h2>Trump administration blocked from suspending Snap benefits for millions of Americans<\\/h2>  <p>Two federal judges issued back-to-back rulings on Friday in separate cases ordering the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> to use contingency funds to continue paying for food stamps during the government shutdown.<\\/p> <p>A federal judge in <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/rhode-island\\\">Rhode Island<\\/a> blocked the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> from suspending all food aid for millions of Americans, in a case brought by a group of US cities, non-profit organizations and a trade union.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/judge-blocks-trump-snap-suspension\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Trump can\\u2019t require citizenship proof on the federal voting form, judge rules<\\/h2>  <p><strong>Donald Trump<\\/strong>\\u2019s request to add a documentary proof of citizenship requirement to the federal voter registration form cannot be enforced, a federal judge ruled today.<\\/p> <p>US district judge <strong>Colleen Kollar-Kotelly<\\/strong> in Washington DC sided with Democratic and civil rights groups that sued the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> over his executive order to overhaul US elections. She ruled that the proof-of-citizenship directive is <strong>an unconstitutional violation of the separation of powers<\\/strong>, dealing a blow to the administration and its allies.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/judge-ruling-trump-citizenship-proof-vote\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Justice department seeks 2020 election records from Georgia county<\\/h2>  <p>Trump\\u2019s justice department on Thursday <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.documentcloud.org\\/documents\\/26209719-fulton-county-crt-letter\\/?mode=document\\\">asked election officials<\\/a> in Fulton county, Georgia, to turn over records related to the 2020 election, a request that underscores how the administration is trying to revive one of the president\\u2019s biggest falsehoods about the election he lost five years ago.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.cnn.com\\/2023\\/06\\/20\\/politics\\/georgia-fulton-county-2020-elections-investigation\\\">Investigators have cleared<\\/a> Fulton county of malfeasance in 2020. Nonetheless, a Republican majority on the board voted to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/georgiarecorder.com\\/2024\\/08\\/08\\/georgia-election-boards-right-wing-faction-revisits-fultons-2020-presidential-election\\/\\\">reopen<\\/a> the investigation last year.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/trump-georgia-2020-election-records\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Harrison Ford lays into Trump on climate<\\/h2>  <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/film\\/harrisonford\\\">Harrison Ford<\\/a> has said that <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/donaldtrump\\\">Donald Trump<\\/a>\\u2019s assault on measures to address the climate crisis \\u201cscares the shit out of me\\u201d and makes the US president among the worst criminals in history.<\\/p> <p>In a blistering attack, Ford told the Guardian Trump \\u201cdoesn\\u2019t have any policies, he has whims. It scares the shit out of me. The ignorance, the hubris, the lies, the perfidy. [Trump] knows better, but he\\u2019s an instrument of the status quo and he\\u2019s making money, hand over fist, while the world goes to hell in a handbasket.\\u201d<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/environment\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/harrison-ford-donald-trump-climate-crisis\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>How Stephen Miller is creating an \\u2018anti-immigration machine\\u2019<\\/h2>  <p>The historic shifts in US immigration under <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/donaldtrump\\\">Donald Trump<\\/a> have been dictated by Stephen Miller, the president\\u2019s <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/usimmigration\\\">immigration<\\/a> czar, who in recent months has turned the state department\\u2019s visa and refugee operations into what some current and former diplomats have described as a personal fiefdom.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/stephen-miller-immigration-trump\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>What else happened today:<\\/h2>  <ul> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/kristi-noem-halloween-immigration-illinois\\\">Kristi Noem, the homeland security secretary, has said she will not suspend the US government\\u2019s aggressive immigration crackdown in Illinois over Halloween<\\/a><\\/strong>, denying a request from the state\\u2019s governor that children might enjoy the holiday \\u201cwithout fear\\u201d.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/trump-republicans-senate-filibuster-shutdown\\\">Trump called on the Senate to scrap the filibuster, so that the Republican majority can bypass Democrats and reopen the federal government.<\\/a> <\\/strong>The Senate majority leader, John Thune, a Republican known for defending Senate traditions, has repeatedly rejected proposals to weaken or remove the 60-vote rule.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p>What is the filibuster and why does Trump want to get rid of it? <strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/31\\/trump-filibuster-explainer-government-shutdown\\\">Here\\u2019s what you need to know.<\\/a><\\/strong><\\/p><\\/li> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/americans-disapprove-trump-east-wing-poll\\\">More than half of Americans disapprove of Donald Trump\\u2019s demolition of the White House\\u2019s East Wing and the construction of a new ballroom<\\/a><\\/strong>, <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.washingtonpost.com\\/documents\\/1d305cca-df33-44a8-ba8d-c98790a67f99.pdf?itid=lk_inline_manual_2\\\">according to a new poll<\\/a> from the Washington Post, ABC News and Ipsos. According to the poll, 56% of the respondents disagree with Trump\\u2019s recent move while 28% are in favor of it. <\\/p><\\/li> <li><p>White House deputy chief of staff <strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/stephen-miller-trump-fbi-agents-injustice\\\">Stephen Miller was the driving force behind a purge of Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agents who had investigated Donald Trump, a new book reveals.<\\/a><\\/strong><\\/p><\\/li> <\\/ul>  <p>Catching up?<em> Here\\u2019s what happened 30 October 2025.<\\/em><\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"atom\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;script src=&quot;https:\\/\\/uploads.guim.co.uk\\/2025\\/01\\/21\\/article-button.js&quot;&gt;&lt;script&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>\",\"wordcount\":\"841\",\"displayHint\":\"qAndA\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-11-01T01:01:09Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-11-01T01:18:43Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3hykk\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/3d29c5de3952fdcd7665b87c11f5c5a61443192b\\/609_0_5000_4000\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"President Trump received a trio of legal setbacks Friday related to the government shutdown and his attempts to tweak voting access in US elections. First, two federal judges issued back-to-back rulings in separate cases ordering the administration to use contingency funds to continue paying for food stamps under the Snap program. One judge in Rhode Island blocked the Trump administration from suspending all food aid for millions of Americans, in a case brought by a group of US cities, non-profit organizations and a trade union. At almost the same time, in a separate but similar case, a judge in Massachusetts ruled that the government must continue to fund the program that helps low-income households stave off food insecurity, in a case brought by the Democratic attorneys general from 22 states and the District of Columbia and three governors who sued the administration. And later Friday, a US district judge in Washington DC ruled that Trump\\u2019s proof-of-citizenship directive to overhaul US elections was unconstitutional. \\u201cBecause our constitution assigns responsibility for election regulation to the states and to Congress, this court holds that the president lacks the authority to direct such changes,\\u201d judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly wrote in her opinion. That\\u2019s a blow to the administration and its allies who have argued that such a mandate is necessary to restore public confidence that only Americans are voting in US elections. Trump administration blocked from suspending Snap benefits for millions of Americans Two federal judges issued back-to-back rulings on Friday in separate cases ordering the Trump administration to use contingency funds to continue paying for food stamps during the government shutdown. A federal judge in Rhode Island blocked the Trump administration from suspending all food aid for millions of Americans, in a case brought by a group of US cities, non-profit organizations and a trade union. Read the full story Trump can\\u2019t require citizenship proof on the federal voting form, judge rules Donald Trump\\u2019s request to add a documentary proof of citizenship requirement to the federal voter registration form cannot be enforced, a federal judge ruled today. US district judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly in Washington DC sided with Democratic and civil rights groups that sued the Trump administration over his executive order to overhaul US elections. She ruled that the proof-of-citizenship directive is an unconstitutional violation of the separation of powers, dealing a blow to the administration and its allies. Read the full story Justice department seeks 2020 election records from Georgia county Trump\\u2019s justice department on Thursday asked election officials in Fulton county, Georgia, to turn over records related to the 2020 election, a request that underscores how the administration is trying to revive one of the president\\u2019s biggest falsehoods about the election he lost five years ago. Investigators have cleared Fulton county of malfeasance in 2020. Nonetheless, a Republican majority on the board voted to reopen the investigation last year. Read the full story Harrison Ford lays into Trump on climate Harrison Ford has said that Donald Trump\\u2019s assault on measures to address the climate crisis \\u201cscares the shit out of me\\u201d and makes the US president among the worst criminals in history. In a blistering attack, Ford told the Guardian Trump \\u201cdoesn\\u2019t have any policies, he has whims. It scares the shit out of me. The ignorance, the hubris, the lies, the perfidy. [Trump] knows better, but he\\u2019s an instrument of the status quo and he\\u2019s making money, hand over fist, while the world goes to hell in a handbasket.\\u201d Read the full story How Stephen Miller is creating an \\u2018anti-immigration machine\\u2019 The historic shifts in US immigration under Donald Trump have been dictated by Stephen Miller, the president\\u2019s immigration czar, who in recent months has turned the state department\\u2019s visa and refugee operations into what some current and former diplomats have described as a personal fiefdom. Read the full story What else happened today: Kristi Noem, the homeland security secretary, has said she will not suspend the US government\\u2019s aggressive immigration crackdown in Illinois over Halloween, denying a request from the state\\u2019s governor that children might enjoy the holiday \\u201cwithout fear\\u201d. Trump called on the Senate to scrap the filibuster, so that the Republican majority can bypass Democrats and reopen the federal government. The Senate majority leader, John Thune, a Republican known for defending Senate traditions, has repeatedly rejected proposals to weaken or remove the 60-vote rule. What is the filibuster and why does Trump want to get rid of it? Here\\u2019s what you need to know. More than half of Americans disapprove of Donald Trump\\u2019s demolition of the White House\\u2019s East Wing and the construction of a new ballroom, according to a new poll from the Washington Post, ABC News and Ipsos. According to the poll, 56% of the respondents disagree with Trump\\u2019s recent move while 28% are in favor of it. White House deputy chief of staff Stephen Miller was the driving force behind a purge of Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agents who had investigated Donald Trump, a new book reveals. Catching up? Here\\u2019s what happened 30 October 2025.\",\"charCount\":\"5307\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"Guardian staff\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL),
(150, NULL, NULL, 'us-news/2025/oct/30/trump-news-at-a-glance-latest-updates-news-today', 'Trump news at a glance: Four Senate Republicans join Democrats to reject global tariffs', 'Despite the rare opposition in the Senate, the House is unlikely to take any similar action – key US politics stories from Thursday 30 October at a glance', 'A (small) number of US Senate Republicans issued a legislative rebuke to president Donald Trump’s world-rattling trade tariffs in a rare alignment with their Democratic counterparts. Four Republicans – Susan Collins of Maine, Mitch McConnell and Rand Paul of Kentucky, and Lisa Murkowski of Alaska – joined the opposition party, voting 51-47 on a resolution to end the base-level tariffs on more than 100 nations that the president put into place via executive order. It was the third time the Republicans have voted alongside Democrats on a tariff resolution this week, previously rallying to end tariffs targeting Brazil and Canada. Going against Trump is rare for Republicans in his second term. But despite the opposition in the Senate, the House is unlikely to take any similar action. House Republicans created a rule earlier this year that will block resolutions on the tariffs from getting a floor vote. US Senate votes to reject Trump’s global tariffs on more than 100 countries The US Senate took a stand against Donald Trump’s global tariffs affecting more than 100 countries on Thursday, voting to nullify the so-called “reciprocal” tariffs. The tariff resolutions are a rebuke to the tariffs themselves and to Trump overstepping his authority and bypassing Congress. Senator Tim Kaine, a Democrat from Virginia, told reporters that the symbolic opposition should catch the president’s attention. Read the full story US will limit number of refugees and give priority to white South Africans The Trump administration is going to restrict the number of refugees it admits into the United States next year to the token level of just 7,500 – and those spots will mostly be filled by white South Africans. The low number represents a dramatic drop after the US previously allowed in hundreds of thousands of people fleeing war and persecution from around the world. The administration published the news on Thursday in a notice on the Federal Registry. Read the full story Trump-Xi meeting: US president says rare earths deal and tariff cut agreed Donald Trump has described crucial trade talks with the Chinese president in South Korea as “amazing”, saying their dispute over the supply of rare earths had been settled and that he would visit China in April. Xi Jinping has not commented on Thursday’s discussions but noted that the economic and trade teams from both countries had “reached a basic consensus on addressing our respective major concerns” during recent talks in Kuala Lumpur, according to Chinese state media. That had “provided the necessary conditions” for their meeting on Thursday, he added. Read the full story New York declares state of emergency to issue food banks $65m amid shutdown New York’s governor, Kathy Hochul, on Thursday declared a state of emergency to free up funds so that she could issue $65m in assistance to food banks because federal funding for the national food stamp program is set to lapse on 1 November. Oregon and Virginia have also issued emergency declarations to release state cash to go towards emergency food assistance as the federal government shutdown imperils Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (Snap) benefits for nearly 42 million Americans. Read the full story Trump directs Pentagon to match Russia and China in nuclear weapons testing Donald Trump has instructed the Pentagon to immediately start matching other nuclear powers in their testing of nuclear weapons, specifically citing Russia and China. In a post to Truth Social, Trump said “because of other countries’ testing programs, I have instructed the Department of War to start testing our Nuclear Weapons on an equal basis. That process will begin immediately.” Read the full story Senate postpones hearing for Trump’s surgeon general pick after she goes into labor The Senate hearing for Donald Trump’s nominee for surgeon general, Casey Means, has been postponed after the nominee went into labor with her first child. Means had planned to make history as the first nominee to appear virtually before the Senate health, education, labor and pensions committee due to her pregnancy on Thursday. Read the full story Illinois governor calls on Trump officials to halt ICE raids for Halloween JB Pritzker, the governor of Illinois, has urged the Trump administration to suspend its immigration crackdown in his state from Friday to Sunday, to allow children to “spend Halloween weekend without fear”. Read the full story What else happened today: US immigration officials have been increasingly detaining people in small, secretive holding facilities for days or even weeks at a time in violation of federal policy, a Guardian investigation has found. Prince Andrew is to leave his home at the Royal Lodge in Windsor after he was served with a formal notice to surrender the lease, Buckingham Palace has said. King Charles has initiated a “formal process to remove the Style, Titles and Honours of Prince Andrew”, who will now be known as Andrew Mountbatten Windsor, the palace said. Andrew did not object to the process, PA reported. US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) agents were involved in a shooting in southern California on Thursday, prompting a federal investigation. The shooting was the second such incident in the region in recent weeks. The wife of a British political commentator who was detained by immigration authorities while on a speaking tour of the US said she had only been able to speak with him for “30 seconds” since he was taken into custody on Sunday over his pro-Palestinian advocacy. Ghosts and goblins might not be the only scary things popping up this Halloween. Prices for the holiday’s most popular candy treats are rising, spooked by Donald Trump’s tariffs and climate change. Catching up? Here’s what happened Wednesday 29 October.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/oct/30/trump-news-at-a-glance-latest-updates-news-today', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/38cdf13709125090f7b47586965b3416d219f08d/467_0_3829_3062/500.jpg', '2025-10-31 08:01:00', '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/trump-news-at-a-glance-latest-updates-news-today\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-31T01:01:00Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Trump news at a glance: Four Senate Republicans join Democrats to reject global tariffs\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/trump-news-at-a-glance-latest-updates-news-today\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/trump-news-at-a-glance-latest-updates-news-today\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Trump news at a glance: Four Senate Republicans join Democrats to reject global tariffs\",\"standfirst\":\"<p>Despite rare opposition in the Senate, the House is unlikely to take any similar action \\u2013 key US politics stories from Thursday 30 October at a glance<\\/p>\",\"trailText\":\"Despite the rare opposition in the Senate, the House is unlikely to take any similar action \\u2013 key US politics stories from Thursday 30 October at a glance\",\"byline\":\"Guardian staff\",\"main\":\"<figure class=\\\"element element-image\\\" data-media-id=\\\"38cdf13709125090f7b47586965b3416d219f08d\\\"> <img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/38cdf13709125090f7b47586965b3416d219f08d\\/467_0_3829_3062\\/1000.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"The US Capitol on 24 October 2025.\\\" width=\\\"1000\\\" height=\\\"800\\\" class=\\\"gu-image\\\" \\/> <figcaption> <span class=\\\"element-image__caption\\\">The US Capitol on 24 October 2025.<\\/span> <span class=\\\"element-image__credit\\\">Photograph: Aaron Schwartz\\/EPA<\\/span> <\\/figcaption> <\\/figure>\",\"body\":\"<p>A (small) number of US Senate Republicans issued a legislative rebuke to president Donald Trump\\u2019s world-rattling trade tariffs in a rare alignment with their Democratic counterparts.<\\/p> <p>Four Republicans \\u2013 Susan Collins of Maine, Mitch McConnell and Rand Paul of Kentucky, and Lisa Murkowski of Alaska \\u2013 joined the opposition party, voting 51-47 on a resolution to end the base-level tariffs on more than 100 nations that the president put into place via executive order.<\\/p> <p>It was the third time the Republicans have voted alongside Democrats on a tariff resolution this week, previously rallying to end tariffs targeting Brazil and Canada.<\\/p> <p>Going against Trump is rare for Republicans in his second term. But despite the opposition in the Senate, the House is unlikely to take any similar action. House Republicans created a rule earlier this year that will block resolutions on the tariffs from getting a floor vote.<\\/p>  <h2>US Senate votes to reject Trump\\u2019s global tariffs on more than 100 countries<\\/h2>  <p>The US Senate took a stand against Donald Trump\\u2019s global tariffs affecting more than 100 countries on Thursday, voting to nullify the so-called \\u201creciprocal\\u201d tariffs.<\\/p> <p>The tariff resolutions are a rebuke to the tariffs themselves and to Trump overstepping his authority and bypassing Congress. Senator Tim Kaine, a Democrat from Virginia, told reporters that the symbolic opposition should catch the president\\u2019s attention.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/senate-vote-trump-tariffs\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>US will limit number of refugees and give priority to white South Africans<\\/h2>  <p>The <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> is going to restrict the number of refugees it admits into the United States next year to the token level of just 7,500 \\u2013 and those spots will mostly be filled by white South Africans.<\\/p> <p>The low number represents a dramatic drop after the US previously allowed in hundreds of thousands of people fleeing war and persecution from around the world.<\\/p> <p>The administration published the news on Thursday in a notice on the Federal Registry.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/trump-refugee-restrictions-white-south-africans\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Trump-Xi meeting: US president says rare earths deal and tariff cut agreed<\\/h2>  <p>Donald Trump has described crucial trade talks with the Chinese president in South Korea as \\u201camazing\\u201d, saying their dispute over the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/trump-and-xi-meet-in-south-korea-for-crunch-talks-on-trade\\\">supply of rare earths<\\/a> had been settled and that he would visit China in April.<\\/p> <p>Xi Jinping has not commented on Thursday\\u2019s discussions but noted that the economic and trade teams from both countries had \\u201creached a basic consensus on addressing our respective major concerns\\u201d during recent talks in Kuala Lumpur, according to Chinese state media. That had \\u201cprovided the necessary conditions\\u201d for their meeting on Thursday, he added.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/trump-and-xi-meet-in-south-korea-for-crunch-talks-on-trade\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>New York declares state of emergency to issue food banks $65m amid shutdown<\\/h2>  <p>New York\\u2019s governor, Kathy Hochul, on Thursday declared a state of emergency to free up funds so that she could issue $65m in assistance to food banks because federal funding for the national food stamp program is <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/24\\/government-shutdown-food-stamps-snap\\\">set to lapse<\\/a> on 1 November.<\\/p> <p>Oregon and Virginia have also issued emergency declarations to release state cash to go towards emergency food assistance as the federal <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/us-federal-government-shutdown-2025\\\">government shutdown<\\/a> imperils Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (Snap) benefits for nearly 42 million Americans.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/new-york-food-banks-emergency-shutdown\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Trump directs Pentagon to match Russia and China in nuclear weapons testing<\\/h2>  <p>Donald Trump has instructed the Pentagon to immediately start matching other nuclear powers in their testing of nuclear weapons, specifically citing Russia and China.<\\/p> <p>In a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/truthsocial.com\\/@realDonaldTrump\\/posts\\/115460423936412555\\\">post to Truth Social<\\/a>, Trump said \\u201cbecause of other countries\\u2019 testing programs, I have instructed the Department of War to start testing our Nuclear Weapons on an equal basis. That process will begin immediately.\\u201d<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/29\\/trump-pentagon-us-nuclear-weapons\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Senate postpones hearing for Trump\\u2019s surgeon general pick after she goes into labor<\\/h2>  <p>The Senate hearing for <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/donaldtrump\\\">Donald Trump<\\/a>\\u2019s nominee for surgeon general, Casey Means, has been postponed after the nominee went into labor with her first child. Means had planned to make history as the first nominee to appear virtually before the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/us-senate\\\">Senate<\\/a> health, education, labor and pensions committee due to her pregnancy on Thursday.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/casey-means-surgeon-general-senate-hearing\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>Illinois governor calls on Trump officials to halt ICE raids for Halloween<\\/h2>  <p>JB Pritzker, the governor of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/illinois\\\">Illinois<\\/a>, has urged the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/trump-administration\\\">Trump administration<\\/a> to suspend its immigration crackdown in his state from Friday to Sunday, to allow children to \\u201cspend Halloween weekend without fear\\u201d.<\\/p> <p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/illinois-ice-halloween-jb-pritzker\\\"><sub>Read the full story<\\/sub><\\/a><\\/p> <h2>What else happened today:<\\/h2>  <ul> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/ice-hidden-detention-sites\\\">US immigration officials have been increasingly detaining people in small, secretive holding facilities for days or even weeks at a time in violation of federal policy<\\/a><\\/strong>, a Guardian investigation has found.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/uk-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/prince-andrew-leave-royal-lodge-windsor\\\">Prince Andrew is to leave his home at the Royal Lodge in Windsor after he was served with a formal notice to surrender the lease<\\/a><\\/strong>, Buckingham Palace has said. King Charles has initiated a \\u201cformal process to remove the Style, Titles and Honours of Prince Andrew\\u201d, who will now be known as Andrew Mountbatten Windsor, the palace said. Andrew did not object to the process, PA reported.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p>US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) agents were <strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/ice-agents-southern-california-shooting\\\">involved in a shooting in southern California on Thursday, prompting a federal investigation<\\/a><\\/strong>. The shooting was the second such incident in the region in recent weeks.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/sami-hamdi-ice-detention-interview-wife\\\">The wife of a British political commentator who was detained by immigration authorities while on a speaking tour of the US said she had only been able to speak with him for \\u201c30 seconds\\u201d<\\/a><\\/strong> since he was taken into custody on Sunday over his pro-Palestinian advocacy.<\\/p><\\/li> <li><p><strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/30\\/halloween-candy-prices-trump-tariffs-climate-change\\\">Ghosts and goblins might not be the only scary things popping up this Halloween. Prices for the holiday\\u2019s most popular candy treats are rising<\\/a><\\/strong>, spooked by Donald Trump\\u2019s tariffs and climate change.<\\/p><\\/li> <\\/ul>  <p>Catching up?<em> Here\\u2019s what happened <strong><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/oct\\/29\\/trump-administration-news-updates-today-latest\\\">Wednesday 29 October<\\/a><\\/strong>.<\\/em><\\/p>  <figure class=\\\"element element-embed\\\" data-alt=\\\"buttons embed\\\">  <iframe class=\\\"fenced\\\" srcdoc=\\\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;\\/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;script src=&quot;https:\\/\\/uploads.guim.co.uk\\/2025\\/01\\/21\\/article-button.js&quot;&gt;&lt;script&gt;&lt;\\/body&gt;&lt;\\/html&gt;\\\"><\\/iframe> <\\/figure>\",\"wordcount\":\"935\",\"displayHint\":\"qAndA\",\"firstPublicationDate\":\"2025-10-31T01:01:00Z\",\"isInappropriateForSponsorship\":\"false\",\"isPremoderated\":\"false\",\"lastModified\":\"2025-10-31T14:56:06Z\",\"productionOffice\":\"US\",\"publication\":\"theguardian.com\",\"shortUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/p\\/x3hycv\",\"shouldHideAdverts\":\"false\",\"showInRelatedContent\":\"true\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/38cdf13709125090f7b47586965b3416d219f08d\\/467_0_3829_3062\\/500.jpg\",\"legallySensitive\":\"false\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"isLive\":\"true\",\"bodyText\":\"A (small) number of US Senate Republicans issued a legislative rebuke to president Donald Trump\\u2019s world-rattling trade tariffs in a rare alignment with their Democratic counterparts. Four Republicans \\u2013 Susan Collins of Maine, Mitch McConnell and Rand Paul of Kentucky, and Lisa Murkowski of Alaska \\u2013 joined the opposition party, voting 51-47 on a resolution to end the base-level tariffs on more than 100 nations that the president put into place via executive order. It was the third time the Republicans have voted alongside Democrats on a tariff resolution this week, previously rallying to end tariffs targeting Brazil and Canada. Going against Trump is rare for Republicans in his second term. But despite the opposition in the Senate, the House is unlikely to take any similar action. House Republicans created a rule earlier this year that will block resolutions on the tariffs from getting a floor vote. US Senate votes to reject Trump\\u2019s global tariffs on more than 100 countries The US Senate took a stand against Donald Trump\\u2019s global tariffs affecting more than 100 countries on Thursday, voting to nullify the so-called \\u201creciprocal\\u201d tariffs. The tariff resolutions are a rebuke to the tariffs themselves and to Trump overstepping his authority and bypassing Congress. Senator Tim Kaine, a Democrat from Virginia, told reporters that the symbolic opposition should catch the president\\u2019s attention. Read the full story US will limit number of refugees and give priority to white South Africans The Trump administration is going to restrict the number of refugees it admits into the United States next year to the token level of just 7,500 \\u2013 and those spots will mostly be filled by white South Africans. The low number represents a dramatic drop after the US previously allowed in hundreds of thousands of people fleeing war and persecution from around the world. The administration published the news on Thursday in a notice on the Federal Registry. Read the full story Trump-Xi meeting: US president says rare earths deal and tariff cut agreed Donald Trump has described crucial trade talks with the Chinese president in South Korea as \\u201camazing\\u201d, saying their dispute over the supply of rare earths had been settled and that he would visit China in April. Xi Jinping has not commented on Thursday\\u2019s discussions but noted that the economic and trade teams from both countries had \\u201creached a basic consensus on addressing our respective major concerns\\u201d during recent talks in Kuala Lumpur, according to Chinese state media. That had \\u201cprovided the necessary conditions\\u201d for their meeting on Thursday, he added. Read the full story New York declares state of emergency to issue food banks $65m amid shutdown New York\\u2019s governor, Kathy Hochul, on Thursday declared a state of emergency to free up funds so that she could issue $65m in assistance to food banks because federal funding for the national food stamp program is set to lapse on 1 November. Oregon and Virginia have also issued emergency declarations to release state cash to go towards emergency food assistance as the federal government shutdown imperils Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (Snap) benefits for nearly 42 million Americans. Read the full story Trump directs Pentagon to match Russia and China in nuclear weapons testing Donald Trump has instructed the Pentagon to immediately start matching other nuclear powers in their testing of nuclear weapons, specifically citing Russia and China. In a post to Truth Social, Trump said \\u201cbecause of other countries\\u2019 testing programs, I have instructed the Department of War to start testing our Nuclear Weapons on an equal basis. That process will begin immediately.\\u201d Read the full story Senate postpones hearing for Trump\\u2019s surgeon general pick after she goes into labor The Senate hearing for Donald Trump\\u2019s nominee for surgeon general, Casey Means, has been postponed after the nominee went into labor with her first child. Means had planned to make history as the first nominee to appear virtually before the Senate health, education, labor and pensions committee due to her pregnancy on Thursday. Read the full story Illinois governor calls on Trump officials to halt ICE raids for Halloween JB Pritzker, the governor of Illinois, has urged the Trump administration to suspend its immigration crackdown in his state from Friday to Sunday, to allow children to \\u201cspend Halloween weekend without fear\\u201d. Read the full story What else happened today: US immigration officials have been increasingly detaining people in small, secretive holding facilities for days or even weeks at a time in violation of federal policy, a Guardian investigation has found. Prince Andrew is to leave his home at the Royal Lodge in Windsor after he was served with a formal notice to surrender the lease, Buckingham Palace has said. King Charles has initiated a \\u201cformal process to remove the Style, Titles and Honours of Prince Andrew\\u201d, who will now be known as Andrew Mountbatten Windsor, the palace said. Andrew did not object to the process, PA reported. US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) agents were involved in a shooting in southern California on Thursday, prompting a federal investigation. The shooting was the second such incident in the region in recent weeks. The wife of a British political commentator who was detained by immigration authorities while on a speaking tour of the US said she had only been able to speak with him for \\u201c30 seconds\\u201d since he was taken into custody on Sunday over his pro-Palestinian advocacy. Ghosts and goblins might not be the only scary things popping up this Halloween. Prices for the holiday\\u2019s most popular candy treats are rising, spooked by Donald Trump\\u2019s tariffs and climate change. Catching up? Here\\u2019s what happened Wednesday 29 October.\",\"charCount\":\"5808\",\"shouldHideReaderRevenue\":\"false\",\"showAffiliateLinks\":\"false\",\"bylineHtml\":\"Guardian staff\",\"showTableOfContents\":\"false\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', '2025-11-10 01:15:26', NULL);
