e a collection of familiar melodramas, each borrowing from the Troubles for extra dramatic heft. We have the woman in love with a married man who isn\\u2019t honest about his home life, the teacher who goes outside her remit to help a deprived pupil, and the woman whose alcoholic mother\\u2019s final descent to oblivion will surely coincide with the one time her daughter focuses on her own happiness. It\\u2019s all Cushla, with each relationship drawing on the visceral enmity between Catholics and Protestants to rescue it from cliche. But the narrative is constructed with deceptive skill. Small moments and minor characters turn out to be crucial and, as the strands knit together, agonising ironies pile up. Strip down the show\\u2019s politics and they would be dangerously close to a hand-wringing plea for both sides to stop being as bad as each other, to end the violence, and won\\u2019t somebody please think of the children. But the Troubles give Trespasses what it needs. As individuals\\u2019 hopes and feelings are crushed in the gears of events much bigger than them, we feel that pain. \\u2022 Trespasses is on Channel 4 now.\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/arts\",\"pillarName\":\"Arts\"}', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', NULL);
