riginally designed to make it easier to handle goods and money at outdoor markets in cold conditions, when fingers needed to stay free. Denmark\\u2019s mild winters, combined with Copenhagen\\u2019s bike-friendly streets, have made them popular for a different reason \\u2013 allowing an active lifestyle while staying warm (and stylish). Danes ride year-round \\u2013 and their wardrobes reflect it. Clothes need to be practical and functional, yet never at the expense of looking good. \\u201cThe bike culture is huge here and in the last few years the winters haven\\u2019t been as cold as they usually are,\\u201d says Teodora Kolchagova, a brand and communications manager in Copenhagen. \\u201cI love the half-finger gloves \\u2013 Hestra does really nice ones in wool.\\u201d Long puffer jacket The long puffer jacket has faced some undeserved ridicule in Sweden in recent years for its bulky shape and supposed lack of style. Often nicknamed the \\u201cmother sausage\\u201d, it\\u2019s commonly spotted on mothers with young babies out on stroller walks. While Swedish fashion journalist Samanda Ekman argues that the coat represents \\u201canti-fashion\\u201d, author Johanna Schreiber sees it as a symbol of \\u201cwomen\\u2019s liberation\\u201d. The coat\\u2019s popularity is easy to understand: filled with down, it\\u2019s loved for its cocoon-like warmth. \\u201cIt\\u2019s like wearing a duvet,\\u201d says Nina Lindesv\\u00e4rd, an engineer in Stockholm, who wears a black long puffer from Sams\\u00f8e Sams\\u00f8e. \\u201cIt\\u2019s also great for wearing with a skirt underneath \\u2013 or the opposite: sweatpants for a grocery run, and no one will notice. In general, I don\\u2019t like coats that don\\u2019t cover my behind.\\u201d While Lindesv\\u00e4rd\\u2019s jacket is only available for women, Rains does an excellent version for both women and men (my husband has one). Men\\u2019s $550 at Rains Women\\u2019s $550 at Rains Heated socks Unisex Non-compression version on Amazon, batteries included: $444.95 at Amazon Compression version on Amazon, batteries included: $479.94 at Amazon The most traditional Scandinavian sock is the hand-knitted wool sock, worn either on its own or layered over another sock inside shoes. Many families have someone who makes them, but if bought, they usually come from flea markets or directly from local makers. For Juho Pihlajaoja, a freelance stylist in Helsinki, it is a colourful version in blue, green and orange. \\u201cI\\u2019m sitting on a lounge chair post-sauna wearing a pair right now,\\u201d he says. As clothing has become more technical, however, many Scandinavians swear by knee-high socks heated with rechargeable batteries. \\u201cThey are incredible,\\u201d says Sophie Snell, a photographer based in the Swedish ski destination \\u00c5re, of her socks from Lenz. \\u201cIt\\u2019s something I truly can\\u2019t live without \\u2013 or work without, for that matter.\\u201d Lenz socks can be pricey, though Snell says: \\u201cI\\u2019ve had the same pair of socks for almost seven years now and they still haven\\u2019t broken.\\u201d These cheaper alternatives have decent reviews on Amazon \\u2013 though here at the Filter we don\\u2019t have personal experience of them. Amazon rechargeable electric heated socks $79.99 at Amazon Pedestrian safety reflector $14.99 at Amazon They may be tiny, but they make a huge impact during the dark Scandinavian winters. The pedestrian safety reflector, originally invented by Arvi Lehti in Pertteli, Finland, in 1963, is incredibly common. You\\u2019ll see them clipped to jackets and bags everywhere, especially since it gets dark so early in winter. According to the Finnish Road Safety Council, a person is normally visible in car headlights at 50 metres (165ft), but with a reflector, visibility increases to 350 metres (1,150ft). \\u201cIt\\u2019s a typical Finnish thing \\u2013 a little plastic piece you attach to your sleeve, in its most classic form, so you can be seen in the dark,\\u201d says Elna Nyk\\u00e4nen Andersson, a Finnish native now working as a diplomatic counsellor based in Tokyo. \\u201cThere are loads of different designs, but I wear the classic snowflake.\\u201d I haven\\u2019t been able to find this exact snowflake design on sale in the US, but based on my research this is a close contender. Allv\\u00e6rsjakke \\u2013 the \\u2018all-weather jacket\\u2019 Women\\u2019s $530 at Fj\\u00e4llr\\u00e4ven $530 at REI Men\\u2019s $800 at Houdini Sportswear Norway is known for its strong hiking culture, which has also shaped its outdoor fashion. The top priority for Norwegians is to dress according to the weather \\u2013 and there\\u2019s even a local word for the jacket: allv\\u00e6rsjakke, meaning \\u201call-weather jacket\\u201d. Originally a simple raincoat or anorak, it has evolved into a more technical garment, such as a parka, perfect for unpredictable weather. \\u201cI love that it\\u2019s waterproof and lined, so it\\u2019s warm and can handle all kinds of weather,\\u201d says Oslo-based journalist Vibeke Stiansen, who recommends these parkas from Fj\\u00e4llr\\u00e4ven (for women) and Houdini (for men). And like many Scandinavians, she layers underneath it. \\u201cI would typically wear a basic T-shirt or shirt with jeans or tailored trousers, and then a lovely knitted jumper on top \\u2013 either a short one in cashmere or merino wool, or a long, oversized style, preferably in wool or a mohair blend,\\u201d she says. Balaclava Women\\u2019s $155 at Malina Men\\u2019s $139 at Cos This hat, which covers large parts of the head and face, has become a fashion statement. \\u201cI love my balaclavas,\\u201d says Stockholm-based Sara Brandt Zaric, a communications professional, who owns three versions \\u2013 and recommends this one from Malina (for women) and Cos (for men). Cos also does a lovely version for women, but it\\u2019s currently out of stock in the US. \\u201cI think there\\u2019s something beautiful about how a balaclava frames the face,\\u201d says Brandt Zaric.\\u201d Above all, it\\u2019s incredibly practical \\u2013 especially if it extends a bit down over the chest and back, and is easy to pull down. It keeps you warm without any gaps, protecting against both snow and wind. And you don\\u2019t lose it if you pull it back off your head. I hate being cold, yet I still want to dress for work and city life, even when it\\u2019s freezing.\\u201d\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/lifestyle\",\"pillarName\":\"Lifestyle\"}', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', NULL),
(194, 74, 11, 'us-news/2025/nov/09/ghislaine-maxwell-trump-admin-prison-transfer', 'Ghislaine Maxwell reportedly ‘much happier’ after prison transfer by Trump officials', 'Jeffrey Epstein associate, serving 20 years for sex-trafficking crimes, is now in minimum-security federal prison in Texas', 'Longtime Jeffrey Epstein associate Ghislaine Maxwell, who is serving a 20-year prison sentence for sex-trafficking crimes, has reportedly said that she is “much, much happier” after the Trump administration transferred her to a minimum-security federal prison in Texas, according to emails obtained by NBC News. Maxwell, 63, was moved from a low-security prison in Tallahassee, Florida, to the minimum-security Federal Prison Camp Bryan in Texas in August – just days after she was interviewed about the Epstein case by deputy attorney general, Todd Blanche. Blanche is a former personal lawyer for Donald Trump, who had been friends with the late Epstein – a convicted sex offender – before winning two presidencies. The interview with Blanche came as the administration faced growing pressure to release more documents related to the Epstein investigation, a pledge that Trump had made during his campaign. Maxwell’s transfer, which experts described as “unprecedented”, prompted questions as well as outrage from victims of Epstein, who died by suicide while incarcerated in 2019. They wondered why a convicted sex offender like Maxwell was moved to a facility where most of the inmates are serving time for non-violent offenses and white-collar crimes. And now, NBC News has obtained and revealed several emails that Maxwell reportedly sent to friends and relatives after her transfer that expressed delight at her new surroundings. The outlet says the emails were recently shared with the House Judiciary Committee. “My situation is improved by being at Bryan,” she wrote in one email. In another, she wrote: “The institution is run in an orderly fashion which makes for a safer more comfortable environment for all people concerned, inmates and guards alike.” Maxwell described the living conditions, stating that the kitchen “looks clean too – no possums falling from the celling to fry unfortunately on ovens, and become mingled with the food being served”. “I feel like I have dropped through Alice in Wonderlands looking glass,” Maxwell wrote in an email to a relative. “I am much much happier here and more importantly safe.” The food, she said, was “legions better” than where she was held previously. “The place is clean, the staff responsive and polite – I haven’t seen or heard the usual foul language or screaming accompanied by threats leveled at inmates by anyone,” she wrote. “I have not seen a single fight, drug deal, passed out person or naked inmate running around or several of them congregating in a shower!” NBC also reported that in other emails, Maxwell praised the prison camp warden as a “true professional” and also complained about “people selling rubbish stories and making money from their lies”. The emails were reportedly shared with the House judiciary committee after Maryland representative Jamie Raskin, the top Democrat on the committee, sent a letter to the warden of the Texas facility on 30 October. Raskin asked about reports that suggested Maxwell was receiving “VIP treatment” at the prison. He cited a Wall Street Journal article from October, where some current and former inmates said that Maxwell was getting “unusually favorable treatment at times”. In response to NBC’s reporting of Maxwell’s emails, one of her lawyers, David Oscar Markus, told the outlet: “There’s nothing journalistic about publishing a prisoner’s private emails, including ones with her lawyers. “That’s tabloid behavior, not responsible reporting. Anyone still interested in that kind of gossip reveals far more about themselves than about Ghislaine. It’s time to get over the fact that she is in a safer facility. We should want that for everyone.” Maxwell’s brother, Ian Maxwell, also told NBC in an email that messages between him and his sister are “personal and private by their very nature”. If those emails were sent to Congress and a reporter, he said, “then they were stolen and leaked without authorization and represent a breach of intellectual property rights and the fundamental right of all citizens to privacy.” The US supreme court in October declined to hear an appeal from Maxwell on her sex-trafficking conviction.', 'https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/nov/09/ghislaine-maxwell-trump-admin-prison-transfer', 'https://media.guim.co.uk/05a374b0faf9fbc85a4ee28c28cd4f577198adb2/326_0_2393_1916/500.jpg', NULL, '{\"id\":\"us-news\\/2025\\/nov\\/09\\/ghislaine-maxwell-trump-admin-prison-transfer\",\"type\":\"article\",\"sectionId\":\"us-news\",\"sectionName\":\"US news\",\"webPublicationDate\":\"2025-11-09T18:07:18Z\",\"webTitle\":\"Ghislaine Maxwell reportedly \\u2018much happier\\u2019 after prison transfer by Trump officials\",\"webUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/www.theguardian.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/nov\\/09\\/ghislaine-maxwell-trump-admin-prison-transfer\",\"apiUrl\":\"https:\\/\\/content.guardianapis.com\\/us-news\\/2025\\/nov\\/09\\/ghislaine-maxwell-trump-admin-prison-transfer\",\"fields\":{\"headline\":\"Ghislaine Maxwell reportedly \\u2018much happier\\u2019 after prison transfer by Trump officials\",\"trailText\":\"Jeffrey Epstein associate, serving 20 years for sex-trafficking crimes, is now in minimum-security federal prison in Texas\",\"byline\":\"Anna Betts\",\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/media.guim.co.uk\\/05a374b0faf9fbc85a4ee28c28cd4f577198adb2\\/326_0_2393_1916\\/500.jpg\",\"bodyText\":\"Longtime Jeffrey Epstein associate Ghislaine Maxwell, who is serving a 20-year prison sentence for sex-trafficking crimes, has reportedly said that she is \\u201cmuch, much happier\\u201d after the Trump administration transferred her to a minimum-security federal prison in Texas, according to emails obtained by NBC News. Maxwell, 63, was moved from a low-security prison in Tallahassee, Florida, to the minimum-security Federal Prison Camp Bryan in Texas in August \\u2013 just days after she was interviewed about the Epstein case by deputy attorney general, Todd Blanche. Blanche is a former personal lawyer for Donald Trump, who had been friends with the late Epstein \\u2013 a convicted sex offender \\u2013 before winning two presidencies. The interview with Blanche came as the administration faced growing pressure to release more documents related to the Epstein investigation, a pledge that Trump had made during his campaign. Maxwell\\u2019s transfer, which experts described as \\u201cunprecedented\\u201d, prompted questions as well as outrage from victims of Epstein, who died by suicide while incarcerated in 2019. They wondered why a convicted sex offender like Maxwell was moved to a facility where most of the inmates are serving time for non-violent offenses and white-collar crimes. And now, NBC News has obtained and revealed several emails that Maxwell reportedly sent to friends and relatives after her transfer that expressed delight at her new surroundings. The outlet says the emails were recently shared with the House Judiciary Committee. \\u201cMy situation is improved by being at Bryan,\\u201d she wrote in one email. In another, she wrote: \\u201cThe institution is run in an orderly fashion which makes for a safer more comfortable environment for all people concerned, inmates and guards alike.\\u201d Maxwell described the living conditions, stating that the kitchen \\u201clooks clean too \\u2013 no possums falling from the celling to fry unfortunately on ovens, and become mingled with the food being served\\u201d. \\u201cI feel like I have dropped through Alice in Wonderlands looking glass,\\u201d Maxwell wrote in an email to a relative. \\u201cI am much much happier here and more importantly safe.\\u201d The food, she said, was \\u201clegions better\\u201d than where she was held previously. \\u201cThe place is clean, the staff responsive and polite \\u2013 I haven\\u2019t seen or heard the usual foul language or screaming accompanied by threats leveled at inmates by anyone,\\u201d she wrote. \\u201cI have not seen a single fight, drug deal, passed out person or naked inmate running around or several of them congregating in a shower!\\u201d NBC also reported that in other emails, Maxwell praised the prison camp warden as a \\u201ctrue professional\\u201d and also complained about \\u201cpeople selling rubbish stories and making money from their lies\\u201d. The emails were reportedly shared with the House judiciary committee after Maryland representative Jamie Raskin, the top Democrat on the committee, sent a letter to the warden of the Texas facility on 30 October. Raskin asked about reports that suggested Maxwell was receiving \\u201cVIP treatment\\u201d at the prison. He cited a Wall Street Journal article from October, where some current and former inmates said that Maxwell was getting \\u201cunusually favorable treatment at times\\u201d. In response to NBC\\u2019s reporting of Maxwell\\u2019s emails, one of her lawyers, David Oscar Markus, told the outlet: \\u201cThere\\u2019s nothing journalistic about publishing a prisoner\\u2019s private emails, including ones with her lawyers. \\u201cThat\\u2019s tabloid behavior, not responsible reporting. Anyone still interested in that kind of gossip reveals far more about themselves than about Ghislaine. It\\u2019s time to get over the fact that she is in a safer facility. We should want that for everyone.\\u201d Maxwell\\u2019s brother, Ian Maxwell, also told NBC in an email that messages between him and his sister are \\u201cpersonal and private by their very nature\\u201d. If those emails were sent to Congress and a reporter, he said, \\u201cthen they were stolen and leaked without authorization and represent a breach of intellectual property rights and the fundamental right of all citizens to privacy.\\u201d The US supreme court in October declined to hear an appeal from Maxwell on her sex-trafficking conviction.\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/news\",\"pillarName\":\"News\"}', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', NULL);
