le when his bid to buy the Buffalo Bills fell short. The clashes have continued into his presidency: during his first term, he described NFL players protesting against social injustice as \\u201csons of bitches\\u201d. In his second term he has urged the Commanders to revert to their previous racist nickname and attacked the league\\u2019s decision to choose Trump critic Bad Bunny to play the Super Bowl\\u2019s halftime show this season. Will he succeed? This is a man who has already managed to summon up various Trump Towers, Trump Plaza, Trump Steaks, Trump University, Trump Shuttle, Trump Vodka, Trump Taj Mahal, Trump Mortgage and the Donald J Trump Ballroom (to name but a few). Plus, Trump has become adept at getting billionaires to do what he wants of late, while he has found himself given a warmer greeting in the sports world in his second term as president. The route to naming the stadium is a little tricky but Trump has leverage. As president, he oversees the federal agencies responsible for environmental and land-use approvals at the proposed site of the team\\u2019s new stadium, so he could speed up, or slow down, the process if he chose to. \\u201cHe has cards to play,\\u201d one source told ESPN. \\u201cHe can make it very difficult to get this stadium built unless people align with him on the name.\\u201d It should also be noted that the Commanders will not be the ones to name the stadium. The proposed site sits on National Park Service land, and the District of Columbia Council will lease the stadium to the team. Again, Trump can lean on these bodies if he so chooses. \\u201cThe team doesn\\u2019t have the authority. They can\\u2019t name the stadium on their own,\\u201d a source with direct knowledge of the process told ESPN. \\u201cThe city would be involved, and the Park Service would be involved.\\u201d Are other NFL stadiums named after people? They are, but those people tend to be dead. Two of the most famous stadiums in the NFL \\u2013 Green Bay\\u2019s Lambeau Field and Chicago\\u2019s Soldier Field \\u2013 are tributes to people who have passed away. In Green Bay\\u2019s case, the stadium was renamed for the team\\u2019s founder and coach Earl \\u201cCurly\\u201c Lambeau a few months after his death, while the stadium in Chicago was a tribute to US soldiers who had died in the first world war. Washington\\u2019s former stadium was named after a politician, but its name illustrates how it differed from Trump\\u2019s proposal: the Robert F Kennedy Memorial Stadium was renamed as a tribute to the US senator who was assassinated several months beforehand. It\\u2019s also notable that Lambeau and RFK did not lobby to get their names on the stadiums. So which stadiums are named after living world leaders? It should be noted that Trump would \\u2013 probably \\u2013 be out of power by the time the new Commanders stadium opens. But you can draw your own conclusions from living leaders who have their names on stadiums. Cameroon\\u2019s authoritarian leader has the Paul Biya Omnisports Stadium, India\\u2019s authoritarian leader has the Narendra Modi Stadium, Saudi Arabia\\u2019s authoritarian de facto leader has the proposed Prince Mohammed bin Salman Stadium, while Sierra Leone\\u2019s authoritarian leader had the Siaka Stevens National Stadium while he was in power. Hong Kong also went for the Queen Elizabeth Stadium during her reign, but she was a monarch and therefore completely different from Trump.\"},\"isHosted\":false,\"pillarId\":\"pillar\\/sport\",\"pillarName\":\"Sport\"}', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', '2025-11-10 08:16:38', NULL);
